<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli cabinet held a session on Monday to
discuss a further troop withdrawal from the West Bank, but made no
decisions.
</P>
<P>
During the session, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
briefed the ministers on the current talks with the Palestinians
and the United States on the issue. But he failed to convince all
the ministers to accept a U.S. proposal aimed at breaking the
deadlock in the Middle East peace process.
(Israel-Meeting-Withdraw)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- India's 1998-99 budget for defense has increased
by over 14 percent from the previous year's 360.99 billion rupees
(9.38 billion U.S. dollars) to 412 billion rupees (10.70 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Presenting the 1998-99 budget (from April 1,1998 to March 31,
1999) to Parliament here Monday, Indian Finance Minister Yashwant
Sinha said the allocation for Department of Atomic Energy is being
enhanced by 68 percent from 8.28 billion rupees to 13.91 billion
rupees and the allocation for the Department of Space is being
raised by 62 percent from 8.5 billion rupees to 13.81 billion
rupees. (India-Budget)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia and Japan plan to hold joint naval exercises
at the end of next month, the first yet, Itar-Tass news agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The war games will be held soon after naval ships of both
countries take part in festivities in Vladivostok on July 26,
commemorating Navy Day, the agency quoted well-informed sources in
Tokyo as saying. (Russia-Japan-Military)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan said
here Monday that Pakistan and Iran will intensify their joint
efforts for the acceleration of the Afghan peace process.
</P>
<P>
Gohar, who greeted his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi at
the Islamabad airport Monday afternoon, said in a statement that
the Iranian foreign minister's visit "is part of regular high
level consultations between the two countries."
(Pakistan-Iran-FM Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The launching of gyro thrusters of the Russian Mir
space station, originally scheduled for Monday morning, has been
put off until the afternoon, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The gyro thrusters, which automatically maintain the station's
pitch and attitude to ensure that the solar panels generate
maximum power, failed after the station's main computer was
replaced with a new one Sunday. (Russia-Mir-Postponement) 
</P>
</TEXT>
