<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Japan Fails to Live up to Dock-Accord Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. shipping companies say that
Japan isn't living up to its agreement last year to make its ports
more hospitable -- an agreement that led Washington to drop trade
sanctions against Japan and end a chronic trade dispute.
</P>
<P>
Japanese waterfronts remain a trade barrier, U.S. operators
say, because dock work is slow, expensive, inefficient and unduly
influenced by a stevedoring association -- and Tokyo isn't doing
anything about it, the Wall Street Journal reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Those were the same charges that led the U.S. Federal Maritime
Commission last year to impose retaliatory penalties of 100,000
U.S. dollars per ship on Japanese vessels entering U.S. ports.
</P>
<P>
All this was supposed to have been solved after Tokyo agreed in
October to improve foreign access to Japanese ports, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
But today, "in all practical senses, the agreement is dead,"
says a senior executive of a foreign shipping line. Japanese ports
remain as closed as they were before the agreement, he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. shippers say the Japanese government is refusing to step
in. But the Japanese side says that a flawed agreement is not
going to produce any results.
</P>
<P>
Last year's dispute centered on a system called "prior
consultation." Ships docking in Japan had to get clearance from
the Japan Harbor Transport Association, an association of
stevedoring companies, for everything from docking dates to
choice of warehouses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
