<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC's Activities Unaffected by Nuke Tests: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The activities of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) will go ahead as
planned despite the nuclear tests carried out by India and
Pakistan, SAARC Secretary-General Naeem U. Hasan said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua at the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Secretariat, Hasan said that there is no indication that the 10th
SAARC summit will not take place as scheduled in July in Colombo,
Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
He said that other meetings of the seven-nation grouping are
also going ahead as planned. "No member state has asked for any
change," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that he has just returned from Colombo, where he met
with Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga and discussed with
some officials about the arrangements of the summit.
</P>
<P>
"The exact date for the summit will be announced by Sri Lanka,
because they are still in touch with other member countries," the
secretary-general said. "As you know, to get the approval of all
the seven heads of state or government takes some time."
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the Sri Lankan foreign minister will visit
the other six SAARC capitals in one or two days. And he will be
able to announce the final date for the summit when he returns
home.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the SAARC Secretariat is also going ahead with all
the arrangements for the summit, Hasan said.
</P>
<P>
He said he was on a tour of the region days before, and he will
set out again on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Besides, other planned meetings are going on as well, he said.
</P>
<P>
For example, the SAARC commerce ministers met in Geneva as
planned on May 17 before the ministerial meeting of the World
Trade Organization began.
</P>
<P>
And last week, the SAARC Technical Committee on Education,
Culture and Sports met in Thimphu, capital of Bhutan, Hasan said,
adding that the Technical Committee on Health, Population
Activities and Child Welfare will meet in Colombo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Eminent Persons responsible for undertaking a
comprehensive appraisal of SAARC is to have its final meeting on
June 8-11 in the Maldives, the secretary-general said.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, we have had some very important and serious developments
in South Asia in the last two weeks or so, but it is our hope that
these developments will not adversely affect the SAARC process,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan conducted six nuclear tests on May 28 and 30 in
response to the five nuclear tests by India on May 11 and 13,
raising fears of a nuclear arms race in the region and its adverse
impact on the SAARC's future.
</P>
<P>
Hasan said that in its 13 years' existence, SAARC has had some
ups and downs and difficulties. "I'm hopeful that we'll also be
able to overcome the present developments," he said.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in December 1985, aims to establish a South Asian
Free Trade Area preferably by the year of 2001.
</P>
<P>
It now groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
