<HEADLINE> GCC Urged to Improve Industrial Product Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Minister of Commerce
and Industry Abdel Aziz Dekheel Al-Dekheel Monday urged Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states to improve product quality to
live up to international competition.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of a seminar organized by the
Kuwaiti Public Authority of Industry, Al-Dekheel called on GCC
states to focus attention on the industrial sector, one of the
main sources of national income and basis for economic development.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance, comprises
six Arab countries, namely Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Oman, the
United Arab Emirates and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti minister said the GCC states have made achievements
in putting more money into the industrial sector to diversify
sources of national income, create jobs and apply modern
technology to boost social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Doha-based Gulf Organization for
Industrial Consulting showed that investments by the GCC states in
the manufacturing rose to 74.8 billion U.S. dollars in 1996 from
28.5 billion dollars in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The production value of the manufacturing industries rose from
11.2 billion dollars in 1982 to 23 billion dollars in 1996, the
organization said.
</P>
<P>
The contribution of the sector to the gross domestic product in
the GCC states rose from 5.5 percent in 1982 to 9.6 percent in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
