<HEADLINE> Intel Delays Shipment of Next-Generation Chip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corp., the world's largest
computer chip maker, said that it has told its customers that it
is delaying production of its next-generation chip, code-named
Merced, by at least six months.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of computer and software companies tied their fortunes
to the long-awaited chip.
</P>
<P>
The new chip is also crucial to the company's effort to extend
its dominance from personal computers to the most powerful
machines used for high-end workstations and servers, the machines
that run computer networks. Merced had been expected to be
available sometime in the second half of 1999. On Friday, however,
Intel said it has to delay volume production of the
microprocessor, the heart of the computer, to mid-2000, due to the
complex involved in the new chip.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the delay is not expected to have a dramatic
impact on computer makers, most of which will offer high-end
systems based on chips other than Intel's.
</P>
<P>
Intel chips power nearly 90 percent of PCs worldwide. The
Merced is intended to help Intel make inroads into the high-end
computer market.
</P>
<P>
The chip will be Intel's first to use a 64-bit instruction
set, to process more computing instructions, vs. the current
32-bit instruction set in the higher-end Pentium II.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
