<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac's Remarks in Lebanon "Not Helpful": Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac's
remarks that Israel should withdraw from south Lebanon without
conditions were "not helpful" for a solution to the problem, a
senior Israeli official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Israel did not impose any conditions on its withdrawal from
south Lebanon while adopting the United Nation Resolution 425,
said David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Bar-Illan insisted that
the U.N. resolution itself, which calls for an "immediate and
unconditional" Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon, "does have a
provision for a security arrangement."
</P>
<P>
Israeli cabinet endorsed the resolution on April 1, two decades
after it was adopted and then ignored, saying it wanted to quit
the 15-kilometer-deep self-declared security zone along the border
if Lebanon government made arrangements to prevent cross-border
guerrilla attacks against Israel's northern areas.
</P>
<P>
The offer was rejected by Lebanon, which insisted that Israeli
troop pullout should be unconditional under the U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Beirut, the third in just two years, the
French president said on Sunday that he hoped for the
implementation of resolution 425 "immediately and without any
condition."
</P>
<P>
His position was utterly in line with those of Lebanon and its
powerful ally Syria, who held that the peace process on Lebanese
and Syrian tracks could not be separated and Israel should return
the Golan Heights it captured from Syria in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
Bar-Illan, however, reiterated that Israel would not agree to a
unilateral withdrawal from south Lebanon unless security
arrangments are worked out with Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Without such arrangments, the battlefield would only be pushed
back south Lebanon to Galilee in northern Israel, he said, adding
that "it would be meaningless."
</P>
<P>
In an earlier response to Chirac's remarks, Bar-Illan said on
Sunday that Israel would continue its effort to persuade Lebanese
government to facilitate the withdrawal of Israeli troops
and to make necessary arrangements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Expresses Deep Concern over Lack of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday expressed deep concern over lack of functioning
government in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
"I urge all of the leaders to demonstrate their political will
to reach a settlement through practical and constructive
compromise," Annan said in his latest report on the situation in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Haiti has been without a Prime Minister since June 1997, and
with a virtually paralyzed parliament since this January.
Efforts to break the deadlock have been largely unsuccessfully.
</P>
<P>
"Haitian political leaders must quickly take concrete steps
to end the political deadlock, both with regard to the
installation of a new government and the holding of free and
fair elections to be organized by a new, credible Professional
Electoral Council so that the country' fragile democracy can be
consolidated and pressing national issues resolved," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The report warned that the political crisis is having a
destabilizing effect on Haiti's fledgling democracy, while also
harming economic activity and jeopardizing international assistance.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General reported progress in modernizing the
Haitian national Police, but also expressed concern about
continuing reports of human rights violations, corruption and
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
"Professionalizing the police has to be complemented by a
functioning judicial system, for if the Haitian National Police
is to function effectively, it must do so within the context of
a credible judicial reform " said the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
He once again urged the Haitian authorities to move forward
expeditiously in the areas of judicial reform and called on the
international community to provide the necessary assistance in
that regard.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pakistan's Economy on Track for Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's economy has shown some
encouraging signs in the first 10 months of the 1997-98 fiscal
year (July 1,1997 to June 30, 1998) with inflation down to 8.2
percent, trade balance improved by 54 percent and both
agricultural and industrial sectors recorded increase.
</P>
<P>
In the backdrop of these positive achievements, the annual
growth rate of Gross Domestic Product is estimated to grow by 5.4
during the current fiscal year, which will be the highest in the
last several years.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures released by the government,
Pakistan's inflation rate, which has been running at double digit,
has declined to 8.2 percent in the first 10 months of the current
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
It is by no means a good news for the general public as this
south Asian nation has achieved a single digit inflation rate for
the first time in the last four years. And the 8.2 percent
inflation rate is also the lowest since the beginning of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture sector, which consists of about 25 percent of the
country's GDP, has recovered and is estimated to grow by 5.9
percent in the outgoing fiscal year, surpassing the target of 5.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
During the 10-month period, Pakistan has achieved cotton
production of 9.2 million bales. It may fail to meet the budget
target of 10 million bales due mainly to bad weather condition in
the last several months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Industrial output during the first three
quarters of the current fiscal year has registered a 7.2 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
The worrisome factor facing the government is the chronic
shortage of revenue collection. The target for the 1997-98 revenue
collection by the Central Board of Revenue (CBR) was fixed at
324.0 billion rupees (7.4 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, because of the unsatisfactory economic performance
during the first half of the current fiscal year, the revenue
target was later revised to 304.3 billion rupees (6.9 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
During the first 10 months of the current fiscal year the
revenue collection stood at 225.02 billion rupees (5.1 billion
dollars), which was 73.9 percent of the revised target.
</P>
<P>
Exports during the first 10 months of the current fiscal year
have increased by 4.6 percent, rising from 6.81 billion dollars to
7.13 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The growth in exports has come primarily from a 20.2 percent
increase of primary commodities exports and a 34.4 percent
increase in exports of other goods.
</P>
<P>
However, exports of textile manufacture, which consists of 60
percent of Pakistan's foreign exchange earnings, declined by 0.4
percent while other manufactures recorded nominal increase.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports during the same period have declined by
almost 13 percent to 8.45 billion dollars. Major decline comes
from industrial sectors including machinery, petroleum, textile as
well as agri-chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The balance of trade during the 10-month period stood at 1.32
billion dollars as against 2.90 billion dollars during the
corresponding period of the previous fiscal year. This amounts to
a 54.2 percent improvement in trade balance
</P>
<P>
The current account balance during the period has also improved
by almost 66 percent and stood at 1.127 billion dollars as against
3.288 billion dollars in the comparable period of the 1996-97
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Major contribution to this improvement has come from a
significant improvement in the trade balance, an 18.4 percent
increase in workers' remittances which stood at 1.175 billion
dollars and 54.9 percent increase in the inflow of Resident
Foreign Currency Deposits registering 1.485 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign private investment during the first three quarters of
the outgoing fiscal year amounted to 639.9 million dollars as
against 633.7 million dollars achieved in the same period of last
fiscal year, registering an increase of one percent.
</P>
<P>
Within foreign private investment, foreign direct investment
(FDI) has decreased by 2.7 percent from 448.4 million dollars to
436.1 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Almost 65 percent of FDI has come into the power, oil and gas,
and chemical, pharmaceutical and fertilizer sectors.
</P>
<P>
It is noteworthy that despite the East Asian crisis and general
loss of confidence in Asian markets by foreign portfolio
investors, Pakistan has succeeded in attracting 203.8 million
dollars of portfolio investment during the first three quarters of
the current fiscal year which is 10 percent higher than the
comparable period of last fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
