<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Increases In April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Boosted by the largest increase
in commercial projects since last Summer, the U.S. construction
spending rose in April for the fifth consecutive month, the
Commerce Department reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 0.8 percent increase, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 630.1 billion U.S. dollars, followed gains of 0.1 percent in
March and 0.8 percent in February, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
Construction spending has been growing since late last year,
supported by low U.S. interest rates caused as a side effect of
Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The April growth was led by a 2.3 percent gain in
nonresidential commercial projects, to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 167.3 billion dollars. Advances in construction of
offices, hotels and motels and shopping centers helped offset a
decline in spending on industrial buildings.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, residential construction increased 0.9 percent, to a
seasonally adjusted rate of 285.8 billion dollars. However, it
didn't match the 1.5 percent advance in March and it was the
smallest since November.
</P>
<P>
Single-family construction advanced 1.2 percent and apartment
construction, 1.6 percent. Remodeling spending slipped 0.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
Government construction increased 0.4 percent, only the second
gain in six months, to a seasonally adjusted rate of 136.3 billion
dollars. Increases in spending on schools and highways and streets
helped offset drops at military facilities, housing projects and
hospitals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
