<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan is committed to extending all efforts of the United Nations
to relieve the suffering of the quake-affected Area in
Afghanistan, his spokesman said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A strong earthquake on Saturday hit Badakshan and Takhar
Provinces in Northeast Afghanistan, a region that has been
recovering from the severe effects of an earthquake which took
place in February.
</P>
<P>
The quake on Saturday was measured 7.2 magnitude, with death
toll estimated at 2000 to 3000, although the official figure was
not available.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. official told reporters here that the quake "was
certainly bigger" than the one in February which killed over a
thousand people. He said the magnitude of the latest one can be
compared with the 1988 Armenian earthquake and the large Iranian
quake in 1990.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. assessment team arrived in the affected area on Sunday
and five U.N. humanitarian flights are expected from Pakistan's
Islamabad to Afghanistan's Faisabad late today, the official said.
</P>
