<HEADLINE> High Production Costs Seen as Uganda's Bottleneck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has put the high costs of production resulting from poor
infrastructure as one of the main problems his country faces in
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Addressing parliament session Monday afternoon, Museveni also
named poor management, tax evasion and deliberate dumping of some
imports and smuggling as the bottlenecks for development.
</P>
<P>
To improve management of revenue collection, he said, the
Uganda Revenue Authority has been restructured and the revenue
collection system is going to be computerized.
</P>
<P>
He described the improvement of road network as a necessity
for economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has enough equipment to improve feeder roads in 39
districts and four million U.S. Dollars are still needed to buy
equipment for the remaining districts, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for trunk roads, he noted, work on the Sironko-Kapchorwa
Road has already been started and two others are expected to
begin by September 1999.
</P>
<P>
The government is also committed to improving efficiency in
the generation, transmission and distribution of utilities across
the country. This will be achieved by privatization, expansion
and utilization of efficient technology.
</P>
<P>
The Uganda Electricity Board should reduce its operation costs
by reducing the tariff, he added.  
</P>
