<HEADLINE> 10 Village Guards Killed in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Ten Turkish village guards were
killed Monday by rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK) in an armed clash in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
The clash took place near Guneyaka village of Beytussebap town
in Sirnak Province bordering northern Iraq, the semi-official
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
After the incident, Turkey's security forces launched an
operation in the region to pursue the rebels, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a war against the Turkish government
since 1984 for independence in the southeast, during which more
than 35,000 people have been killed.
</P>
<P>
The militants have been seeking shelter in northern Iraq After
Baghdad was rendered ineffective to exercise control there in the
1991 Gulf War. About 2,500 of them frequently launched
cross-border attacks on targets inside Turkey from northern Iraq.
</P>
