<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Decides to Narrow Appeal to Attorney-Client </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and
his lawyers decided on Monday to tell the Supreme Court they will
drop a claim of executive privilege and try to block a top aide's
testimony only on attorney-client privilege grounds.
</P>
<P>
Attorney-client privilege states that clients do not have to
disclose what they discussed with their lawyers, and may prevent
others from disclosing such confidential information.
</P>
<P>
The switch in legal tactics aims at countering Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr's move last week seeking to bypass the
normal appeals process and ask the Supreme Court to settle the
dispute over the testimony of two White House aides in the Monica
Lewinsky probe.
</P>
<P>
The final decision was made at a meeting Monday between the
president and top lawyers, according to White House spokesman Mike
McCurry. McCurry said White House lawyers would file the response
today.
</P>
<P>
"The filing will confirm the president will not appeal the
district court's ruling on executive privilege," McCurry said.
"The filing will also confirm the legal counsel's intention to
appeal the ruling on attorney-client privilege."
</P>
<P>
The decision removes the barriers for Starr to question
immediately one of the aides, Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
The president's appeal will focus on blocking some testimony by
Clinton confidant Bruce Lindsey on grounds that he was functioning
as a lawyer and his testimony is covered by the right of clients
to keep their legal conversations confidential.
</P>
<P>
Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr said in a prepared speech
in Charlotte, North Carolina, today that such an appeal was
wrongheaded because courts have already concluded that government
lawyers don't have such a privilege in criminal cases involving
public officials.
</P>
<P>
A federal judge ruled last month that Lindsey and Blumenthal
had to answer grand jury questions they had previously refused.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors want to question Blumenthal about his sources of
derogatory information about Starr's office, and Lindsey on a
variety of matters, including his contacts with witnesses in the
Lewinsky probe.
</P>
<P>
In her ruling last month, U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway
Johnson rejected the attorney-client claim based on earlier
rulings that while government lawyers have such a privilege it
can't be used to block their testimony before a federal grand jury
about possible criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
On executive privilege, Johnson ruled that while the privilege
applied to the disputed testimony, prosecutors' interest in the
information outweighed the president's right to keep his
conversations confidential.
</P>
<P>
White House lawyers reportedly viewed the latter interpretation
as a partial victory, and that led to the president's decision
Monday to focus the appeal solely on attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
Earlier there were reports quoting White House communications
director Ann Lewis as saying, "I don't think what Ken Starr is
looking for is assistance. What he's trying to find are more
reasons to explain why he really can't prove a case."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laxities in Army Lead to Rebel Head's Escape: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
Monday blamed the Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) for their
internal laxities which led to the narrow escape of Joseph Kony, the
head of the rebels of Lord Resistance Army.
</P>
<P>
He made public this blame in a 18-page speech delivered to
parliament in Kampala.
</P>
<P>
He said some weaknesses on some levels of command, especially
at the middle level, are at least partly responsible for the
recent narrow escape of Kony when he was trapped by the army.
</P>
<P>
He promised to press the commanders to resolve all their
internal laxities and end this problem.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, the rebels suffered heavy losses in their
encounters with the army. The first group of rebels headed by
Vincent Otti lost 32 members in their first encounter with the
UPDF soldiers and the second group spearheaded by Kony himself
lost 30 members in four consecutive encounters.
</P>
<P>
Since the rebel groups entered Uganda from their Sudan base a
few weeks ago, some 150 of them have been killed and about 100
have surrendered with guns.
</P>
<P>
The Kony rebels, estimated at 800, entered Uganda in May for
food and medicines. They used landmines to loot vehicles on roads
in Kitgum and Gulu Districts instead of abducting civilians as
they had done before.  
</P>
</TEXT>
