<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Govt to Close Schools with Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
will not hesitate to close all private schools which do not have
adequate facilities while turning schools as a source of making
profit.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister of Education and Culture, Juma Kapuya made the
remarks over the weekend during a graduation ceremony at Ununio
and Kunduchi Islamic Schools in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Kapuya said he was irked by some schools are short of basic
services and equipment while the schools' management do not make
any efforts to solve these problems.
</P>
<P>
He said a lot of private schools lack libraries, buildings for
teachers, dispensaries, drainage system, toilets, playgrounds,
kitchens and dining halls.
</P>
<P>
The schools are operating against the education and culture
ministry's procedures and instructions, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged such schools to work out proper plans to
solve these problems, otherwise they will be closed down or
handed over to those who will be able to run these schools.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Kapuya insisted that the government will not
allow schools to collect miscellaneous fees at will.  
</P>
