<HEADLINE> Arab FMs Meet Ahead of Euro-Med Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of nine Arab
countries along the Mediterranean met here Monday to devise a
common strategy for the forthcoming European-Mediterranean
Partnership summit in Palermo, Italy.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries are Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, Egypt, Tunisia,
Mauritania, Algeria, Morocco and the Palestinian National
Authority. They are to hammer out a common stance against Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Arabs are going to Palermo amid Israeli efforts to separate
politics from economy and gain more economic benefits," Lebanese
Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries will ask the summit to use economy as a weapon
to force Israel to respect the principles of the peace process, he
added.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope that the summit will allow everyone to express
ideas on all issues.
</P>
<P>
The Euro-Med summit is due to be held in Palermo on June
3-4. It involves European Union's 15 members, the nine Arab
countries, and Israel and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The program, which is aimed at creating a free-trade zone, was
launched in Barcelona, Spain in 1995. 
</P>
