<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Refinery Exempted from Japan's Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan's will suspend its loans
to Pakistan for its six nuclear tests, but an oil refinery would
be exempted, the Japanese embassy in Washington said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The project can't be subject to our sanction measures," an
embassy spokesman said, because the deal was finalized in late
March and Japan's economic sanctions only apply to new loans.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Export-Import Bank and four other banks have agreed to
lend 500 million U.S. dollars to Pakistan's Pak-Arab Refinery Ltd.
to build an oil refinery by the year 2000 in Mahmood Kot, 900
kilometers north of Karachi.
</P>
<P>
Japan, Pakistan's largest aid donor and trading partner, has
suspended certain new loans to Pakistan because of its nuclear
tests. 
</P>
