<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Worried about the increasing
disorder at the medical market in Lagos, the economic and
business center of Nigeria, the state government has launched a
sanitization exercise.
</P>
<P>
The government said Monday it will continue to close down
illegal patent medicine stores, destroy fake drugs and prosecute
offenders until the state is free from their activities.
</P>
<P>
The state health ministry will not condone or compromise on
the matter, said Michael Ogungbesan, the Commissioner of Health,
quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"The task force (on health) gives periodic reports on the
situation and new methods of combating the menace," said the
commissioner, who appealed to the public to furnish them with
information on the presence of fake drugs to help the crack-down
exercise.
</P>
<P>
He also urged citizens of the state to report illegal
hospitals and quack medical practitioners to the appropriate
authorities for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
"We may not be able to locate such hospitals. It is the public
that patronizes them so they should let us be aware," the
commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to reports of increasing tuberculosis cases in the
state, the commissioner said it is untrue that the disease "has
reached an epidemic level".
</P>
<P>
The health ministry and its agencies are doing everything
possible for control the spread of the disease and "so far, we
are succeeding," he added.
</P>
<P>
The official daily New Nigerian reported about a week
ago an upsurge in the number of TB cases in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a hospital source, it said the development was
indicative of the fact that the infection is on rampage.
</P>
