the G-7 nations are meeting over how to provide aid to Russia.
</P>
<P>
"There is an active dialogue now ongoing between U.S.
officials, officials from other G-7 countries, international
financial institutions to look at further reforms that will be
necessary, what financial needs there are in light of the current
market conditions," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said Sunday that the U.S. will
endorse additional international aid for Russia to stablize its
ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement, Clinton expressed U.S. support for aid to
Russia from such multinational institutions as the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
"The United States endorses additional, conditional financial
support from the international financial institutions, as
necessary, to promote stability, structural reforms and growth in
Russia," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He said he based his decision on his conversations with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and consultations among other U.S. and
Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
But the Clinton administration has offered few specifics about
the emergency aid and has said bilateral support from Washington
was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
"As President Clinton made clear, the action would be through
the multilateral system," Rubin said. 
</P>
