<HEADLINE> Tanzania Introduces Parole System for Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye officially launched parole national and
regional boards Monday here with a call to the public
to supplement government efforts to fight crimes.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye said under the newly introduced system, prisoners who
have shown signs to repent will be set free under the tight
scrutiny by the society where they will be pardoned if they
behave like good citizens.
</P>
<P>
"Under the parole program, citizens have a vital role to play
especially in monitoring the prisoners that have been set free,
and offering needed assistance to the prisoners which will enable
them to fit in the society," he said.
</P>
<P>
The premier said the parole system is adopted by the
government in an effort to reduce crimes in the society by
involving the citizens and easing congestions in prisons.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the representatives of prisons nationwide and
members from non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and religious
leaders, the premier said it will be important if the board will
operate in fairly and transparently.
</P>
<P>
Onel Malisa, Commissioner of Prisons, said establishment of
the parole system is in line with the Parole Board Act passed by
the parliament in 1994. The board members are appointed by
President Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
"Under the parole system, the prisoners set free will be given
a grace period. If they do not change or show signs to change
their behaviors, they will be brought back to serve their
imprisonment terms," Malisa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
