<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The new headquarters of the former
rebel force, the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) started operation in Luanda Monday.
</P>
<P>
Antonio Dembo, Vice-Chairman of UNITA said at the opening
ceremony of the headquarters that operation of the UNITA's new
office in the capital indicates UNITA's willingness to continue
its efforts for the peace process in the country.
</P>
<P>
Dembo urged all Angolans to join hands in their struggle for a
real national unity and reconciliation, so as to win the total
independence, liberty and the enhancement of people's welfare.
</P>
<P>
Blondin Beye, United Nation's special envoy to Angola, said at
the ceremony that the operation of the new UNITA headquarters is
a historic event, indicating that UNITA has said bye to the past
and is determined to co-operate with the government.
</P>
<P>
After recalling all the major steps in the peace process, he
said that war is not the best way to solve problems, and the
correct way is to lay down their arms and get onto the way of
peace.
</P>
<P>
He urged UNITA to continue its effort for the final peace of
Angola, and make contribution the stability and development of
southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Despite the opening of the headquarters, UNITA leaders,
including Chairman Jonas Savimbi have not moved to Luanda yet,
and the former UNITA headquarters of Bailundo and Andulo are
still under UNITA's control.
</P>
<P>
The moving of the UNITA headquarters to capital Luanda is one
of the major tasks laid out in the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol.
</P>
