<HEADLINE> Nigerian Court Rejects Cases Against Abacha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Federal Court of Appeal in
Lagos Monday rejected two cases against the adoption of the Head
of State, General Sani Abacha by the country's five political
parties as their consensus candidate for the general election.
</P>
<P>
The court said it does not have the jurisdiction over the
cases filed by Alhaji Mohammed Yusuf, former national police
head, and Tunji Braithwaite, a Lagos-based lawyer.
</P>
<P>
Both Yusuf and Braithwaite had sought to run the presidential
elections scheduled for August 1 on the platform of the
Grassroots Democratic Movement, but the party, like the four
others, decided in April to have Abacha as their flag bearer.
</P>
<P>
Braithwaite said he will appeal to the supreme court.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Federal High Court in Lagos threw out a similar
case filed by the lawyer Gani Fawehinmi on the same ground: lack
of jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, General Abacha is expected to arrive in Lagos for a
one-day working visit Tuesday. It is said to be his second visit
since 1994 to the former national capital, where his alleged
presidential ambition receives the strongest opposition.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed media reports said Abacha may finally speak out on
his presidential candidacy when he comes to Lagos Tuesday. He has
been silent on the issue all the time. 
