<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Cuts Rosneft Auction Starting Price by Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government decided
Monday to auction 75 percent of shares in the Rosneft oil company
at a starting price of 9,862 million rubles (1,644 million
dollars), almost half the original starting price of May.
</P>
<P>
The move, ordered by Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, follows a
failed tender on May 26 when nobody bade. The total starting price
then, including investment obligations, was 2.5 billion dollars,
Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
The failed auction of Rosneft was seen by some as a factor that
contributed to Russia's financial crisis late last month.
</P>
<P>
The Kiriyenko government has since then indicated that it would
lower the starting price to "take into consideration the true
situation on the market and the fall in world oil prices."
</P>
<P>
A number of Russian and foreign companies have expressed
interest in acquiring a 75 percent plus one share stake in
Rosneft, the last Russian oil giant still in state hands.
</P>
<P>
They include the alliance of Gazprom, Lukoil and Royal
Dutch/Shell, the Unexim-British Petroleum group and the
Yukos-Sibneft together with their financial groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
