<HEADLINE> Annan Concerned About Eritrea-Ethiopia Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan is very concerned at the report about clashes between
Eritrean and Ethiopian troops since Sunday, his spokesman said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Annan recalled that he and others were offering assistance in
resolving the dispute between the two countries and stresses the
need for maximum restraint to ensure that the situation does not
deteriorate, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief sent letters Friday to the prime ministers of
Eritrea and Ethiopia, calling for full cooperation with the
regional and international diplomatic efforts now underway, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general also wrote to Djibouti President Hasan
Gouled Aptidon, thanking him for his mediation efforts assisted by
Secretary-General of the Organization of African Unity Salim
Ahamed Salim, according to the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
