<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's IT Market Could Be Hurt by U.S. Sanctions: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 1 (Xinhua) -- India's information technology
(IT) market could be significantly impaired by U.S. economic
sanctions following the Asian country's recent nuclear test,
according to International Data Corp., a U.S. market research
firm.
</P>
<P>
While full details on the breadth of these sanctions have yet
to be announced, IDC said, there is the potential for strong
impact on the Indian IT market, as well as for U.S. IT vendors
with operations in or exports to India.
</P>
<P>
The United States, India's largest trading partner, was joined
by Japan, Germany and Australia in announcing tough economic
measures.
</P>
<P>
"How it will affect India's IT market is heavily tied into the
duration of the sanctions and the definite possibility that they
could extend to high-technology materials," said Lisa Cosmas, an
IDC Asia/pacific analyst.
</P>
<P>
In that instance, Cosmas said, not only will the Indian economy
suffer, but its IT market will experience a considerable slowdown
in growth. "U.S. IT vendors that have been increasing their
investments in this market will also feel the repercussions of
these sanctions," she said.
</P>
<P>
India represents the second-fastest growing IT market in the
Asia-Pacific. Prior to the imposition of economic sanctions, IDC
Asia/Pacific had predicted that from 1997 to 2002, India would
experience a compound annual rate of 15.6 percent, and domestic IT
spending would reach 5 billion U.S. dollars by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, IDC said, computer software and services exports
contributed 1.14 billion dollars to India's IT industry in the
financial year 1996-1997.
</P>
<P>
Today, approximately 60 percent of software services sourced
from India are by U.S. companies. Digital, Dun and Bradstreet,
General Electric, IBM and Oracle represent just a few companies
that have significant software facilities located in India.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
