<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Meets Jordanian Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President (PNA) Yasser Arafat met with Jordanian Minister of
Justice Riyad Shakaa Tuesday in Gaza on the latest situations in
the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of Palestine radio reported that Arafat discussed
with Shakaa the possibility of holding an Arab summit to
coordinate Arab stance on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
They also touched on ways of promoting the bilateral relations,
the radio said, without elaborating on details.
</P>
<P>
Shakaa was in Gaza for a one-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PNA Minister of Planning and International
Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath told the radio that "we want our Arab
summit to back us during our important battle with Israel and the
Arab nations should exert more efforts for convening such a
summit."
</P>
<P>
"Through the summit, we will tell our Arab nations, Israel and
the United States our patience will no longer continue before the
Israeli arrogance and attempts to destroy the peace process,"
Sha'ath said.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the Palestinians and Israelis have been
stalled since March 1997 when Israel started work on a Jewish
settlement in East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as the
capital of their future independent state.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has called for an emergency Arab summit to work out a
unified Arab stance to confront Israeli intransigence and hardline
policy on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Intensive consultations have been made among Arab countries,
most of which have reportedly agreed to attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
Israel, however, has accused the PNA of violating the Oslo
Accords signed between the two sides by seeking to convene the
summit.
</P>
<P>
"The only way to resolve the differences between Israel and
the PNA is through direct talks, as prescribed in the Oslo
Accords," advisor to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
David Bar-Illan told the Israel Radio on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
