<HEADLINE> Ung Huot Returns From Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's First Prime Minister
Ung Huot returned home Tuesday from his two-day official visit to
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot and his party were welcomed by high-ranking government
officials and envoys of some foreign countries including Chinese
Ambassador to Cambodia Yan Tingai, at the airport.
</P>
<P>
On arrival, Ung Huot told reporters that his trip was
successful.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot said his talks with Vietnamese Premier Phan Van Khai
had achieved common views on the border issues between Cambodia
and Vietnam and they both believed the problem would be solved
before the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Vietnamese immigrants to Cambodia, Ung Huot, also
minister for foreign affairs and iternational cooperation, said
the issue would be settled according to Cambodia's immigration law
and nationality law.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the overlapping maritime areas between the two
countries, Ung Huot said the Vietnamese government had agreed to
hold two-party talks between them, or tripartite talks among
Cambodia, Thailand and Vietnam, to resolve the problem.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Ung Huot held talks with leaders of the
Vietnamese government and exchanged views on issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
The two side also signed three agreements, on land transport,
combating drug trafficking and information cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
