<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Stamp Market Mired in Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- In sharp contrast to the brisk
salesroom atmosphere in Guardian's autumn stamp auction in 1997,
its spring sale last month was cold and cheerless.
</P>
<P>
With almost the same amount and quality of stamps sold,
Guardian, one of China's largest oldest art auction companies,
this spring earned only two-thirds of the transaction value of
last autumn's sales.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing's stamp market, nearly all the more than 10 stamp
versions issued this year are sold now at prices lower than their
face values, except for that for the Year of the Tiger (1998) and
that for the centennial of Peking University (now called Beijing
University).
</P>
<P>
China's first gold foil stamp sheet, issued last year to
celebrate the return of Hong Kong to the motherland, was also
left out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
The sheet, sold for 120 yuan, which was a lot more than its
face value of 50 yuan, was pushed as high as some 400 yuan in
the market last year but now can be obtained for a mere 80
yuan.
</P>
<P>
"The sluggish market now is an inevitable result of the
over-heated market last year," said an official from the Chinese
Philately Federation, who refused to give his name.
</P>
<P>
He said that many stamp collectors have been trapped by the
gold foil stamp sheet, while some big dealers, who have made
profits from the sheet, have shifted their capital to other
investment areas, such as the stock market and real estate.
</P>
<P>
More people seem to attribute the sluggish market to a rise of
the stamps' face value and enlarged circulation. The circulation
of the gold foil sheet, for example, has reached 20 million and
drawn more than two billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Cai Jiaming, a local stamp collector, said that he hopes that
the World Stamp Exhibition to be held in Beijing in autumn 1999
will stimulate the market, which is not expected to pick up in the
near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
