<HEADLINE> Williams, Majoli Put out of French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 2 (Xinhua)-- Eighth-seeded Venus Williams's road to
the semi-finals was blocked by top-seeded Martina Hingis on
Tuesday after losing 6-3, 6-4 in the quarterfinals at the French
Open.
</P>
<P>
But Williams' compatriot, No. 2 seed Lindsay Davenport, moved
into the last four with a 6-1, 5-7, 6-3 victory over defending
champion Iva Majoli.
</P>
<P>
Hingis raced to a 3-0 lead with her deft touch and clever court
sense but Williams broke her in the fifth game for 3-2 as Hingis
twice double-faulted. Hingis then broke right back for 4-2 and
held on to win the set.
</P>
<P>
Williams had a chance to break Hingis for 2-0 in the second set
racking up three break points before Hingis won five straight
points to take the game.
</P>
<P>
In the crucial game of the set, Hingis broke Williams for 4-3
again on two double faults, this time by Williams.
</P>
<P>
Hingis has a masterful touch, moving opponents around the court
with precise groundstrokes while Williams count on purely power.
</P>
</TEXT>
