<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Cabinet Discusses Measures for Austerity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The federal cabinet of Pakistan
met here Tuesday to discuss various measures for austerity,
economic self-reliance and increasing productivity and national
income in various sectors.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet meeting chaired by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif was
informed that Pakistan had achieved the wheat target this year
with a production of 19 million tons, according to a press release
by the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
The wheat production is 16 percent more than that of last year
and the target for next year is likely to be fixed at 22.3 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, efforts are being made to increase the production of
palm oil and seed oil within the country to decrease reliance on
imported oil.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet held that the high rates of growth shown in the
agricultural sector should be further enhanced and maximum
facilities and incentives should be provided to farmers to enable
them to play a due role in the national construction.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided in principle to enhance agricultural
credits as well as to introduce modern technologies and farm
mechanization in this regard.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the cabinet agreed that efforts should be
made to improve performance of the industrial sector. The main
focus of these efforts would be on small and medium enterprises
which could play a very significant role in promoting the
country's exports.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also discussed policy framework for introducing
austerity, economy and efficiency in government sector as well as
in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
It also approved specific measures with respect to austerity
and efficiency in Pakistan's diplomatic mission abroad.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet meeting also approved reduction in public holidays
from 20 to 11 a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
