<HEADLINE> Kiriyenko Expects Business From French Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko said Tuesday he hoped his coming visit to France will
promote economic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass news agency reported that on the eve of his visit,
Kiriyenko told reporters, "I hope there will be businesslike
specific talks with French colleagues on the entire range of
bilateral relations."
</P>
<P>
During the visit scheduled for June 3-4, Kiriyenko is expected
to meet French President Jacques Chirac, Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin and other French leaders, and discuss Russia's integration
into the world economy and Russian's relations with the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries will also focus their discussions on
ways to bolster their business ties, notably in high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the potential is high for cooperation in the
peaceful use of nuclear energy, in the space industry, aircraft
construction and automobile manufacture.
</P>
<P>
The Russian premier said the trade volume between Russia and
France is showing signs of growth after stablizing from the
troughs of the early nineties.
</P>
<P>
Russia is determined to railroad itself towards the market
economy, he said. He believed Russian and French businessmen would
find common ground and step up their cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
