<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls Want Rodman to Beat Malone in Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Dennis Rodman can seize a chance
to steal spotlight in the NBA Finals if he gets smart.
</P>
<P>
His matchup against the Utah Jazz tough-man Karl Malone will go
a long way toward determining the outcome of the best-of-seven
series starting this evening at the Delta Center in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
But he has to do something otherwise than what he had done
during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Rodman was a non-factor in last season's finals, as he averaged
a pale 2.3 points and 7.7 rebounds in only 27 minutes an outing.
</P>
<P>
He was in constant foul troubles, and he lost his temper and
let his frustration get him frequently duriong the game. The Bulls
didn't really need him last year because they had Brian Williams.
</P>
<P>
Rodman proved his record against the Indiana Pacers in the
Eastern Conference finals, averaging 4.7 points and 9.9 rebounds
after averaging 6.1 points and 16.1 rebounds through the playoff's
first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls know they can't win their sixth NBA championship if
Rodman doesn't have a turnaround against the Jazz. He could very
likely get his starting job back because he has to be the primary
defender on Malone.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not concerned about Dennis," coach Phil Jackson said.
"Dennis comes to play. He is struggling with coming off the bench
and accepting what his role was last series. He will have a
different role in the games coming up. It is going to be his turn
to shine."
</P>
<P>
Malone, who averaged 23.8 points and 10.3 rebounds in last
season's NBA Finals against the Bulls, is a difficult matchup for
Rodman.
</P>
<P>
Rodman can't get into Malone's head and take him out of his
game, and he can't muscle him around. All Rodman can do is make
him work hard and play him tough in the low post so the Bulls
don't have to double-team him all of the time.
</P>
<P>
"Dennis' value in this series is going to be measured in his
energy," Michael Jordan said."He didn't have the greatest series
against Utah last year and we still won. But I think his energy
will be needed this year. I don't anticipate any problems from
Dennis. He knows what he has to do."
</P>
<P>
What Jordan said is right. Rodman knows where his position is
and is ready to do big to prove his image. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
