<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: U.N. Sanctions Damage Libyan Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Libya has incurred losses of up to
23.56 billion U.S. dollars in all economic tracks since the United
Nations Security Council imposed sanctions in March 1992.
</P>
<P>
The economic and trade sectors alone have lost up to 5.856
billion dollars, according to a bi-annual report prepared by the
Arab Economic Unity Council (AEUC) of the Cairo-based Arab
League.
</P>
<P>
Harm done to the spheres of agriculture, industry, maritime
wealth and financial dealings, the drop in the export-import activity
and the freeze of Libyan funds abroad have attributed to the losses
in the economic and trade sectors.
</P>
<P>
Also at jeopardy were the energy, industry, mining and health
sectors, said the AEUC report.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been living under an air, arms and diplomatic embargo
after Tripoli had failed to hand over for trial two Libyan
suspects, charged with involvement in the 1988 bombing of a Pan-Am
airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland. The explosion killed some 270
passengers.
</P>
<P>
The report will be presented by the council's Secretary
General, Hassan Ibrahim, to its 67th ministerial session which
will be held here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will precede a visit to Egypt by Libyan leader
Muammar Gaddafi, who has postponed his trip to Cairo from the
first week of June to later this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
