<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Amend Law on Rural Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China is to amend the Law on the
Organization of Villagers' Committees, the introduction of which
ten years ago brought full democracy to over 900 million Chinese
farmers for the first time in history, a Ministry of Civil Affairs
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The law, which was adopted by the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature, in
November 1987, abolished the age-old practice in China's vast
countryside that officials were hand-picked by governments at
higher levels.
</P>
<P>
It requires all members of the Villagers' Committee, the formal
village leadership, to be directly elected by the entire village,
and grants the farmers the right of self-government.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Mingliang, director of the Grassroots Power Building
Department under the Civil Affairs Ministry, said that, thanks to
the law, farmers in more than 60 percent of China's nearly one
million villages are now practising self-government, which means
that they not only elect their own village leadership, but also
monitor its operation and have a say in all major village affairs.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that over the past decade most villagers'
committees across the country have held three direct elections.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhang noted, since the law was formulated in the early
years of China's building of its legal system, it is far from
perfect and has many weak points.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, the principle of "Four Democracies,"
which has been proved by experience over the past decade to be the
core of villagers' self-government, is not written into the
existing law.
</P>
<P>
Besides the democratic election (of the villagers' committee),
the other three democracies are democratic decision-making
(in village management), democratic management (of village
affairs) and democratic supervision (by the villagers over the
village leadership).
</P>
<P>
Though it has defined the basic principles for the direct
elections of villagers' committees, the existing law has failed to
provide for any concrete electoral methods and procedures, Zhang
added.
</P>
<P>
The existing law also overlooks possible problems that could
hamper the democratic nature of the elections, such as bribery,
fraud, disruption of the electoral order or influence from
officials at higher levels, and makes no relevant stipulations, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The amendment is expected to add good experience from all over
the country for promoting rural democracy to the existing law, and
make the law more powerful and applicable," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The amendment has been listed in the NPC Standing Committee's
legislation plan for this year, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bilateral Agreement to Punish World Cup Thugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (xinhua) -- English hooligans guilty of
soccer-related offences at the World Cup in France will be
punished by further court actions back home under a new bilateral
agreement, British Home Secretary Jack Straw said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Straw said thugs who offend in France could now be charged in
England or Wales in addition to any other punishment they might
receive from the French judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Straw, addressing the headquarters of the football unit of the
National Criminal Intelligence Service (NCIS), also announced a
continuing increase in the use of restriction orders, which bar
convicted hooligans from travelling to matches abroad.
</P>
<P>
Introduced under the Football Spectators Act 1989, these
restriction orders require their subject to report to a police
station in England or Wales during matches. Failure to do so can
face up to six-month imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Straw said the bilateral agreement with France came into force
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The official also called for fans who had information about
planned hooligan activity to dial the Hooligan Hotline, based at
the NCIS and relaunched for the World Cup by Straw in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
