<HEADLINE> Bird Says His Return up to Pacers Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Larry Bird, coach of the Indiana
Pacers, is considering to quit his position after the team failed
to enter the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
Bird, in his first season coaching at any level, guided and
inspired his players brilliantly this season in pushing the
Chicago Bulls to the limit before losing 88-83 in Game 7 of the
Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
All of the team's ace players except center Rik Smits and point
guard Travis Best, who will be free agents this summer, are under
contract for at least the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
The Pacers are deep and experienced. They could be ready to
replace the Bulls as the top team in the Eastern Conference unless
Bird leave the team.
</P>
<P>
Bird signed a five-year contract in May 1997, however, he has
not committed to next season after winning the title of the NBA
Coach of the Year.
</P>
<P>
"I'll talk to my players and see if they like what we're trying
to do," Bird says. "They can come to me and say they want somebody
else to lead them. I can move on. It's been an enjoyable
year. I'll talk with some of the players in the next couple of
days and get their feelings. Whether I'm back or not, I don't
know."
</P>
<P>
Six Pacers -- Reggie Miller, Smits, Mark Jackson, Derrick
McKey, Antonio Davis and Dale Davis -- were on the teams that lost
in seven games in the Eastern Conference finals to New York in
1994 and Orlando in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Pacers President Donnie Walsh has said he expects Bird to
return because "he is a man who fulfills his commitments."
</P>
<P>
Bird promised many times during the regular season that he
wanted to take the Pacers where they never have been. The team has
not reached the NBA Finals since joining the league for the
1976-77 season.
</P>
<P>
Bird did pretty well in coaching the team which set a record of
58 victories in the regular season, the second-best record in the
Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
It's all about winning the championship," Bird said." I didn't
get them where I wanted to take them."
</P>
<P>
But it is a clear fact that Bird can do much better next season
as the coach if he remains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
