<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Iran for Early End to Afghan Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Iran on Tuesday
stressed the need for an early end to the long-running Afghan
conflict and agreed to intensify their efforts for the promotion
of the intra-Afghan dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The message was contained in a press release issued here by the
Foreign Ministry after a meeting between Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan and his visiting Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian delegation led by Kharrazi arrived here Monday for
a two-day visit, the first by a high-level foreign delegation
after Pakistan's detonation of six nuclear devices on May 28 and
30.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Gohar, Kharrazi also met with Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs Siddique Khan Kanju Tuesday. During the meetings,
discussions were held on a wide range of issues including
bilateral relations and the Afghan situation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries underscored their determination "to further
develop close, mutually-beneficial ties in all fields of common
interest," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Afghan issue figured prominently in the talks.
The two sides agreed to intensify their efforts for the promotion
of the intra-Afghan dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The situation in South Asia in the aftermath of Indian nuclear
tests was also discussed.
</P>
<P>
It was emphasized that in view of the "grave threat" posed to
Pakistan's security as well as the Indian leadership's threat to
impose a military solution on Kashmir, Pakistan had no choice but
to take "appropriate measures" for the restoration of the
strategic balance in the region and "deterrence of nuclear and
conventional aggression."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif met with the Iranian delegation
earlier Tuesday and stressed that Pakistan was left with no option
but to take appropriate steps to offset the grave threat posed to
its security by India's nuclear tests and its "belligerent
attitude" on the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister affirmed his country's commitment
to a close Iran-Pakistan relationship as well as its readiness to
work with Pakistan for an early end to the Afghan conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
