<HEADLINE> Turkey Warns of Damage to Turkish-French Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkey Tuesday warned of a damage to
the friendly Turkish-French ties if France could not handle the
alleged Armenian genocide motion in a cautious manner.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is closely following the issue because it is related to
Ankara's stance toward France, Turkish Foreign Ministry
spokesman Necati Utkan told a daily press briefing.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the French National Assembly unanimously adopted a
motion stating that "France publicly recognizes the Armenian
genocide of 1915." The motion now goes before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has denied that the deaths of some 1.5 million Armenians
in Ottoman Turkey between 1915 and 1923 constituted genocide,
insisting that massacres occurred on both sides as the result of a
civil war.
</P>
<P>
"France is not an enemy of Turkey. If such a motion is
adopted, then the interests of both countries will be severely
harmed," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that all allegations regarding the so-called
Armenian genocide by Turks in 1915 were "unfounded" and France
should deal with this matter in a responsible way.
</P>
<P>
With regard to this issue, Turkey has said that thousands of
Armenians and Turks were killed in fighting between the two sides
in what is now eastern Turkey and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to stacks of history books and archives on the
rostrum, Utkan said that making a study of these historical
materials would prove that the alleged Armenian genocide is an
out-and-out lie.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Parliament has decided to lodge a strong protest
against the French legislature over the controversial motion put
forward by Socialist deputies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
