<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inspection of Boeing-737s Finds No Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- No problem was found when China
conducted a special safety inspection on 18 Boeing-737 airliners
with a total flight time of over 20,000 hours, according to an
official from the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC).
</P>
<P>
This was in response to an order by the Federal Aviation
Administration (FAA) of the U.S., issued on May 10, to launch
an urgent inspection of all Boeing-737 airliners that have flown more
than 40,000 hours, said Zhang Yongsheng, deputy director of the Air
Worthiness Department of the CAAC, in an exclusive interview with
Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Before this, an FAA official found two small holes caused by a
short circuit in wiring "sleeves" near an oil tank on the wings of
a Boeing-737 belonging to U.S. carrier Continental Airlines. The
event aroused great concern in the civil aviation sector.
</P>
<P>
China now has 141 Boeing-737 airliners, accounting for
nearly one third of the national air fleet. The oldest, however,
has so far flown only 32,000 hours, so China-run Boeing-737
airliners do not fall within the range of inspection required by
the FAA, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
But China has still inspected some airliners with a flight time
of more than 20,000 hours as of May 15, focusing on their tank
parts, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
This is a high-degree consideration for air travelers. Safety
is the top priority of civil aviation, he added.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the sound safety situation of China's civil
aviation to a set of strict and scientific management rules that
have reached world standards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
