<HEADLINE> Beijing to Raise Minimum Living Standard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital will raise the
minimum living standard of its urban residents per person from
190 yuan to 200 yuan starting next month, the municipal government
announced today.
</P>
<P>
This means that Beijing's urban families with a per-capita
monthly income of less than 200 yuan will be subsidized by the
municipal or district finances.
</P>
<P>
Beijing first implemented the minimum living standard system on
July 1 1996, when the standard was set at 170 yuan per person per
month. The minimum living standard was lifted to 190 yuan on June
1 of last year.
</P>
<P>
Some 11,000 Beijing families have benefited from the welfare
system, with the authorities extending more than two million yuan
in subsidies each month, according to an official at the Municipal
Civil Affairs Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Beijing began issuing grain and edible oil relief
cards to low-income residents on December 1, 1996. Card holders
have since then been receiving 20 yuan-worth of grain or edible
oil each month. Currently, more than 22,000 residents hold such
cards.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the grain and edible oil relief cards
will be maintained after the latest readjustment in the minimum
living standard.
</P>
<P>
An official survey indicates that beneficiaries of the welfare
system and the card program are mainly jobless people, laid-off
workers and workers in inefficient enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
