<HEADLINE> Chinese Smokers to Join International Quit-Smoking Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A veteran smoker in China may get
10,000 U.S. dollars if he wins an international contest for
smokers who quit the habit.
</P>
<P>
Lin Yafu, a 43-year-old resident of Liuzhou City, in southwest
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, won a lottery to qualify
for the 1998 International Quit and Win Contest during a world
conference on health promotion in Puerto Rico later this month.
</P>
<P>
Lin, a chain smoker for 25 years, has kept away from cigarettes
for the past month, as the contest rules stipulate.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time for China, with the world's biggest
population of smokers, to take part into the international
contest. It was initiated by the Finnish Center for Health
Promotion, aiming to encourage more smokers to quit the habit.
</P>
<P>
About 12,000 smokers in Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai
participated in the contest in 1996. A Tianjin participant became
the final winner of 5,000 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
