<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China aims to increase its trade
volume with Saudi Arabia to five billion U.S. dollars-worth within
five years, stated Shi Guangsheng, minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark while holding talks with Osama Faqih,
commerce minister of Saudi Arabia, today.
</P>
<P>
Briefly reviewing the bilateral commercial ties, Shi said
that they lagged far behind the development of their economies.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the economies of the two nations are highly
complementary.
</P>
<P>
China hopes to make use of Saudi Arabia's oil resources, while
Chinese consumer goods are very popular in the Saudi market, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he hoped efforts by both sides would bring the
bilateral trade relations to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
Shi welcomed Faqih's suggestion that the two sides should start
cooperation in the petrochemicals industry and technology
exchanges, and that Chinese enterprises should take part in mining
projects and power grid construction in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed China's undertaking of projects, export of
labor services and investment in Saudi Arabia, and extended mutual
support on the issue of World Trade Organization entry.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, whose trade volume with China reached 1.68
billion U.S. dollars-worth last year, was China's largest trade
partner in the Western Asia and Africa region.
</P>
<P>
Present at the talks were Saudi entrepreneurs accompanying
Faqih on his China visit, and representatives from Chinese trade
companies in the fields of petrochemicals, textiles and grain.
</P>
<P>
