<HEADLINE> Italian PM to Visit Iran to Improve Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
is to visit Iran within this month, Renewing the role of Rome as
the pioneer among European countries to better ties with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Though the date for Prodi's visit has not yet been finally set,
the daily Abrar reported Tuesday that his two-day trip might start
on June 18.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Prodi's coming visit marks a turning point in
Rome-Tehran ties as well as the relations between Iran and the EU
following the Rushdie issue in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Iran-EU ties have been strained since 1989 after Iranian
supreme leader Ayatollah Musavi Khomeini issued a religious decree
to sentence British writer Salman Rushdie to death for his
controversial novel "The Satanic Verses."
</P>
<P>
Prodi will be the highest-ranking official from the EU member
states to visit Iran since then.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to meet Iranian President Mohammad Khatami,
Parliament Speaker Nateq Nouri and Chairman of the State
Expediency Council Hashemi Rafsanjani, the Abrar said.
</P>
<P>
During Prodi's visit, the two countries will sign a number of
agreements to boost bilateral trade and encourage investments in
Iran.
</P>
<P>
In March, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini kicked off the
exchange of visits at ministerial level between the EU and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Dini's visit came shortly after the EU lifted ban on
ministerial visits to Tehran imposed on Iran in April last year
after the Berlin court accused Iranian leaders of sponsoring
terrorist assassinations.
</P>
<P>
Recently, industrialists, investors and businessmen from EU
member countries have rushed to Tehran to find opportunities of
economic cooperation with the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
"Italy is a pioneer member of the EU and will do its best to
make Iran's relations with Europe better and better," Italian
Ambassador to Iran Lodovico Ortonag said last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
