<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ``Search For Dark Matter May Raise Space Knowledge to New Level'' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- He Zuoxiu, a 72-year-old
academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, was very excited
to learn that the Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer will be launched
tomorrow morning.
</P>
<P>
For 20 years he has been involved in research into dark matter
in space, and the launching of the spectrometer will provide a
golden opportunity to find out whether or not dark matter exists.
</P>
<P>
Besides common matter that gives out or reflects light,
scientists believe that another kind of matter that does not give
out or reflect light exists in space, and is called dark matter.
</P>
<P>
Scheduled to be launched into outer space by a shuttle at 06:10
tomorrow from the U.S., the Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer is
designed to detect the presence or otherwise of anti-matter and
dark matter in space.
</P>
<P>
"If the existence of dark matter can be confirmed," said the
research fellow, "then research into theoretical physics will be
greatly pushed forward and the knowledge of mankind about space will
be raised to a new level."
</P>
<P>
He said that the theory of dark matter was first put forward
by a scientist from the former Soviet Union, and China's research
in this regard started shortly after that, and even earlier
than in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
But, according to the academician, currently only about ten
scientists are doing research on this subject, mainly in Beijing
and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"We can feel dark matter because it has gravitation. We believe
that it is the majority of the matter in space, and its weight
accounts for over 90 percent of the universe," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The more knowledge we have about space, the more opportunities
we will have to improve mankind's future," he said, adding that
the more knowledge we have about it, the more significance space
will have for mankind.
</P>
<P>
The cosmic ray detector will stay in outer space for about ten
days, but the initial results will probably not be obtained until
one or two years later, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Flays Officials for Poor Tax Collection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Tuesday flayed the tax service for its failure to boost tax
revenue and warned of a new crackdown on major nonpayers.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency quoted Yeltsin as saying that tax
collection had got "not better, but worse, especially over the
past two months."
</P>
<P>
"Where can we get the money to pay miners, teachers, doctors?"
Yeltsin asked at the Kremlin while meeting with Deputy Prime
Minister Viktor Khristenko, Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov,
newly-appointed State Tax Service chief Boris Fyodorov and the
heads of the tax police and customs service.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin castigated Fyodorov's predecessor, Alexander Pochinok.
He said he had dismissed him Friday for "complete inertia in his
work."
</P>
<P>
Tougher measures would be taken against the directors of major
debtor enterprises, Yeltsin said, warning that he would "dismiss
them from their posts by presidential decree and open up criminal
cases."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a cabinet's program to boost federal revenues has
been approved by the president.
</P>
<P>
After the Kremlin meeting, Khristenko said the president
strictly demanded proper control over the implementation of the
program.
</P>
<P>
The government would report daily to the president on its
implementation and would inform the public about it.
</P>
<P>
Khristenko said one of the stipulations set by the president
was that there should be no privileges or postponements of
payments, no indulgences.
</P>
<P>
The main failure in the past two months, Khristenko said, was
in the collection of taxes, not other payments.
</P>
<P>
Khristenko said the courts were now considering several cases
linked with tax defaults.
</P>
<P>
Fyodorov, the head of the State Tax Service, said, "Failure to
pay taxes is not simply an indecency, but a criminal offense."
</P>
<P>
Fyodorov said his main task is not to think up some greatly
superior steps, but to toughly implement the government's
decisions, and to do it in a way that was never used before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
