<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intellectual Property Rights Essential to Economic Recovery, Says HKSAR Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Improving protection of
intellectual property rights is vital to speeding the economic
recovery in Asia, Director of Intellectual Property Stephen Selby
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the three-day World Intellectual Property
Organization (WIPO) Asian Regional Symposium, which started here
on Monday, Selby pointed out that intellectual property related
investments in Asia amounted to billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The present economic difficulties in Asia have forced us all
to take a long, hard look at how best to exploit our economic
resources," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said: "More and more economies in Asia now recognize
creative talent, inventiveness, and even folklore as a national
resource, and are looking to boost their protection of
intellectual property as a way to maximize their economic
potential."
</P>
<P>
"The symposium is a timely opportunity to exchange ideas. The
symposium attracts prominent intellectual property figures from
around the world. It is aimed at exploring the technical aspects
of implementing the Agreement on the Trade related Aspects of
Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPS)," he said.
</P>
<P>
TRIPS is one of the subsidiary agreements of the Agreement
Establishing the World Trade Organization (WTO) and binds the 132
WTO members. TRIPS also expands the scope and protection of
intellectual property rights to trade related issues.
</P>
<P>
"Effective enforcement is the key to complying with the TRIPS
agreement," Selby said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been in de facto compliance since 1996, but
compliance is not mandatory until January 1, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0103 </DOCNO>
