<HEADLINE> Cambodian Constitutional Council Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Constitutional Council
was sworn in Tuesday under the chair of Chea Sim, president of the
National Assembly, who was authorized by King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
Seven members of the nine-member council attended the
swearing-in ceremony in the palace, despite the absence of the two
other members.
</P>
<P>
The council is an influential legal body, which will have the
power to review laws passed by the National Assembly and to
determine whether laws comply with the spirit of the
Constitution. It can also rule on election disputes and interpret
the outcome of the elections.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the council has paved way for the elections
scheduled for July 26.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear why Chau Sen Cocsal Chhum and Son Sann, the
oldest members of the council who were named by King Sihanouk,
were absent, but speculation is that they were not satisfied with
the council.
</P>
<P>
Just before the ceremony, Chau Sen Cocsal Chhum released a
statement claiming that the council's creation was illegal.
</P>
<P>
The creation of the Constitutional Council had been delayed by
squabbles over its political composition. Prince Norodom Ranariddh
had insisted on opposition representation on the council before he
reached a deal last month with Cambodian People's Party (CPP).
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Council is expected to hold its first formal
meeting on Wednesday to elect the chairman of the council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
