<HEADLINE> Blair in Belfast to Drive Peace Process in N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
arrived in Northern Ireland Tuesday morning in his latest drive to
bring peace to the divided province.
</P>
<P>
Officials said Blair held talks with representatives from the
political parties involved in reaching the peace agreement to
discuss the legislative program for the assembly. This was Blair's
fourth trip to Belfast in five weeks.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was traveling to Belfast from Dublin, where
he held talks with Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern over
bilateral relations and Northern Ireland peace deal on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Belfast, Blair would also hold talks with
the Democratic Unionist Party and the United Kingdom Unionist Party
which, along with UUP dissidents, led the referendum opposition to
the pact.
</P>
<P>
Officials said Blair's talks would be of a general "catch-up"
nature, following the May 22 referendum in which a majority of
voters endorsed the peace accord reached on April 10.
</P>
<P>
Although the main Protestant and Catholic parties in Northern
Ireland have backed the deal, some Protestant politicians fear
that Sinn Fein, the political arm of the outlawed Irish Republican
Army (IRA), might get a role in a new ruling executive without the
guerrillas having to surrender their weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
