<HEADLINE> Malaysian Businessman Killed in Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A Malaysian national has been
shot dead in Somali Telecommunications Service (STS) in Mogadishu
as security in the Somali capital has been worsened since
political settlement failed to materialize in May.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitnesses, the Malaysian, Mohamed Rashid Musa,
was killed Monday evening by four men armed with Ak-47 and M-16
assault rifles as he descended from his office in the STS telecom
center, formerly the headquarters of the late Socialist Party
that ruled Somalia for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Musa was heading for the mosque to say his Makhrib prayers at
6:10 p.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
The eyewitnesses also said that the four men had opened fire
on Musa at once to made sure that he was shot dead before
leaving.
</P>
<P>
The assailants of Musa have not been identified, but the
eyewitnesses in the STS center said one of the company's
bodyguards was among the four who killed Musa and that they fled
on a Toyota Land Cruiser driven by a fifth man.
</P>
<P>
People in the area said the Land Cruiser has overturned as
they took to the turn of the former Italian cultural center close
to the former presidential palace of late Siad Barre.
</P>
<P>
All four killers had escaped unhurt, but the neighbors said
the driver who got injured was apprehended by militiamen loyal to
faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the killing is not known. However, there are
speculations that he had some financial quarrel with senior
officials in their joint venture.
</P>
<P>
Musa, a former colonel in the Malaysian army and now the boss
in the telecommunications joint venture, has been the operational
manager of a huge Malaysian telecommunications company known as
KUB that owned 70 percent of the telecom joint venture with the
Somalis who only own the remaining 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Musa had been serving in the United Nations Humanitarian
division during the large U.N. operation in Somalia in 1994-1995
before returning to Mogadishu as a civilian businessman dealing
with Somalis in establishing a telecom company and a Bank known
as Somali-Malaysian Commercial Bank which does little nowadays.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that two Malaysian nationals in Mogadishu are
considering to leave for their home country immediately.
</P>
<P>
As security is worsened in the capital, at least two buses and
three large trucks had been looted Monday in south Mogadishu
resulting in four people dead and several others wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
