<HEADLINE> Egypt: Efforts Being Mobilized to Save Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Arab and international efforts are
being exerted "massively" to salvage the moribund Mideast peace
process, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by the Cairo-based Voice of Arabs Radio by
telephone from Beirut, Moussa said contacts are under way to
convene an Arab summit to break the peace-making stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Intensive discussions have been going on in several Arab
capitals in the past few days to hammer out an agreement on the
agenda, the venue and date of the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
Moussa flew to the Lebanese capital Monday for a two-day
meeting with his Arab counterparts to chart a common strategy on
Israel ahead of a ministerial conference on European-Mediterranean
cooperation in Palermo, Italy, this week.
</P>
<P>
Israel will participate along with the Palestinian National
Authority and 10 other Mediterranean basin countries in the June
3-4 foreign ministers' conference, which will also be attended by
foreign ministers of the 15 European Union member nations.
</P>
<P>
"Europe can play an effective role in promoting the Mideast
peace process within the coming phase," Moussa said. He also
stressed the importance of the United States as one of the
co-sponsors of the peace march.
</P>
<P>
With an annual aid package of 2.3 billion U.S. dollars to the
Middle East, the EU is seeking a greater role in Arab-Israeli
peace-making efforts, which have been largely led by the
U.S. since 1991.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has rejected a recent U.S. initiative aimed at
breaking the year-old impasse in the Palestinian-Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that while Israel still resists the U.S. proposal
of a 13.1-percent second phase Israeli redeployment in the West
Bank, the Palestinians accepted it despite they want 30 percent in
line with the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
In the circumstances, "the world community should have a say in
rescuing the peace drive," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
