<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Hit by Asian Crisis as Current </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A huge 1.2 billion U.S. dollar
blowout in Australia's current account deficit provided proof
Tuesday that there was little Australia could do to escape the
influence of the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) Tuesday announced the
current account deficit widened by 33 percent to a three-year high
of 4.66 billion U.S. dollars in the first three months of calendar
1998, from a revised 3.51 billion U.S. dollar shortfall in the
quarter ending on December 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Today's numbers confirm that the external account is firmly
impaled on a deteriorating trend - which is likely to gather
momentum as the full impact of the Asian slowdown negatively
impacts the export sector over the coming months," John Peters, a
senior economist with Australia's major bank Westpac, said.
</P>
<P>
"We think the export sector in 1998 will notch up its worst
performance since the early 1980s as East Asian demand for
Australian goods and services falls sharply over 1998."
</P>
<P>
The ABS also said Australia's foreign debts had grown to 139.19
billion U.S. dollars in the quarter ending in March from 137.748
billion U.S. dollars in the quarter ending on December 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Su-Lin Ong, a senior economist with Royal Bank of Canada, said
that the deterioration came at a time when demand and overall
growth were moderate, with exports suffering as a result of
external circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"Still, the current account deficit at such levels is clearly
not sustainable and it is likely to continue to come under some
pressure this year, as exports feel the wrath of the Asian
slowdown."
</P>
<P>
The widening also has very serious implications for an already
foundering Australian dollar and most economists said it ruled out
the possibility of the Reserve Bank of Australia changing its
stance on its monetary policy following its monthly board meeting
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
