<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, US Scientists Cooperate in Space Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A three-ton space explorer, jointly
developed by the United States, China and other countries will be
carried into space by the shuttle "Discovery", which is scheduled
for launch at the Kennedy Space Center at 6:30 (Beijing time)
tomorrow morning, the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) announced
here today.
</P>
<P>
The space explorer, known as the "Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer",
is designed to find anti-matter and missing matter in outer space,
according to CAS.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at CAS have produced a key component of the
explorer -- a piece of a permanent magnet, 1.2 m in
diameter, 0.8 m in length and weighing two tons.
</P>
<P>
CAS said that the design, production and environmental testing
of the explorer's mechanical structures have been completed by the
Chinese Academy of Launch Vehicle Technology, meeting the strict
demands for the strength of the mechanical structure when the
shuttle is launched.
</P>
<P>
The Institute of High-Energy Physics of CAS has developed an
anti-coincidence counter for the explorer, which has proved to be
able to stand the pressure caused by massive acceleration and the
violent vibration of takeoff and landing of space vehicles, and
can operate for a long time in space.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 Chinese scientists, along with physicists and
engineers from Russia, France, Italy and other countries, have
been involved in the project, which is presided over by the
Chinese American physicist and Nobel Prize winner Prof. Samuel
C.C. Ting.
</P>
<P>
The explorer will be put into space for tests of its functions
for about ten days and to obtain some basic data, according to
CAS. It will be carried to the American Alpha Space Station in
2002 to serve a working term of three to five years.
</P>
<P>
"The explorer aims to find anti-matter and missing
matter in space, suggested by theoretical physicists 20
years ago, and will help mankind to know more about the
space," said He Zuoxiu, a leading Chinese expert in particle
physics and an academician of CAS.
</P>
<P>
"But scientists will not be able to draw any conclusions
until one or two years later," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time for China and the United States to
cooperate in a major project of space science and technology," said
a CAS spokesman. "It will promote scientific exchanges
and friendship between the two countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
