<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain, Sweden Safest in EU for Motorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain and Sweden are named as
the safest places for motorists among European Union (EU) member
states, while Portugal and Greece are the deadliest.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat, the Luxembourg-based statistical office of the
15-nation union, made the assessment in its road safety report on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It said the road deaths per million people in 1995 in Britain
and Sweden were 64 and 65 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Portugal and Greece, in comparison, registered deaths per
million as 217 and 195 in the same year, when the EU average
dropped to 119 from 148 in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat said that Greater London, Stockholm and Hamburg are
the safest EU regions whereas the Luxembourg province of Belgium
was the worst with 416 road deaths per million people.
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat report said that almost 44,200 people lost their
lives on EU roads in 1995 but this was nearly 14 percent down on
1989. Improvements in road safety between 1989 and 1995 were made
in almost all EU member states with the biggest fall in road
deaths in Finland (by 40 percent), Sweden (by 37 percent) and
Britain (by 32 percent).
</P>
<P>
The biggest rise, however, was 119 percent posted by Greece's
Notio Aigaio. Only two Greek regions -- Peloponnissos and Voreio
Aigoio -- had improvements, Eurostat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
