<HEADLINE> Straitened Students Drop Out in S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of South Korean
students are quitting universities or colleges because they cannot
afford their tuition, a report from the Ministry of Education said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of four-year university students who left schools
reached 18,859 in the first three months of this year, up 59.4
percent from a year ago, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The number of students who failed to register for this spring
semester also rose 21.1 percent to 10,565.
</P>
<P>
More than 400,000 students took a temporary absence from school
from April 1, a 13.3 percent rise over the previous year,
accounting for 27.7 percent of the total student population of the
nation's 155 four-year universities or colleges.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the 11th largest economy in the world, has
been in a financial crisis caused by corporate failures and
non-performing loans of financial institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
