<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Efforts Needed to Prepare for Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- More consultations are needed for
convening an Arab summit to save the Mideast peace process as the
talks between visiting Saudi crown prince and Jordan's King
Hussein Monday produced no tangible results.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the proposed Arab summit, the two sides
"affirmed importance of good preparation which will enhance Arab
solidarity, unify the nations' stands on crucial issues of the
peace process and finally guarantee the success of the summit,"
Jordan's official news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Jordan Times Tuesday said that the efforts
by Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz for an Arab summit
were "bogged down" as he could not iron out the differences
between Syria and Jordan over the its agenda and venue.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of agenda, Syria insists the summit adopt a "clear
and firm" position that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
is responsible for the 16-month-old deadlock of the peace process,
while Jordan does not want to take "drastic steps" to show its
displeasure with Israel, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Israel have been cooperating in the fields of trade,
water supply and airport construction in accordance with their
1994 peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of venue, Syria wants the summit to be held in its
capital Damascus, an idea that Jordan firmly refused, according to
the paper.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's Arabic daily the Ad-Dustour Tuesday quoted Deputy
Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs Jawad Anani as
saying that Jordan prefers a mini Arab summit in Cairo, where the
Arab League is headquartered.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted local political analysts as saying that Jordan
adopted such a hard-line stand in Monday's meeting because it
fears any submission to Syria's ideas might incur anger from its
peace partner Israel and its major aid-provider the United States,
which is the main sponsor of the peace process and reportedly
would not like to see such a summit happen.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi crown prince arrived here Monday from Syria. His
diplomatic efforts followed the visits of Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
to garner support for such a summit aimed at forming a united Arab
front against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations have been deadlocked
since last March over Jewish settlement expansion in occupied
lands and long-delayed Israeli troop withdrawal from the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The lastest U.S. efforts failed to bridge the gap between the
two sides, as Israel rejected a U.S. proposal of 13.1 percent
Israeli troops redeployment in the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
