<HEADLINE> UNITA Keeps Organized Army: UN Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- United Nations special envoy in
Angola Blondin Beye has revealed that the National Union for
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) still keeps some "organized"
army units in certain provinces of the country.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks here on Monday evening at a press
conference. However, he didn't reveal the number of soldiers
under UNITA's control.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the U.N. envoy pointed out that UNITA
has still got non-demobilized forces, echoing the viewpoint of
the Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
Beye stressed that effective solutions must be found to this
problem so as to safeguard the highest interests of the peace
process. The Angolan government and UNITA signed a 1994 Lusaka
peace protocol to start the peace process and end the two decades
of civil war.
</P>
<P>
The news has sparked immediate reactions from the Angolan
government. Deputy Foreign Minister Joao Miranda told the press
that Angola is facing an extremely dangerous situation with
serious retrogression in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the admission of UNITA members to the
national assembly and the government of national unity and
reconciliation in March marks the political solution of the peace
process. However, he said, the settlement of political issues
have not resulted in the settlement of military issues as
expected by people.
</P>
<P>
If the fact that UNITA still keeps its army is not reverted,
Angolan people will suffer once again the disasters.
</P>
<P>
On the establishment of national administration in
UNITA-occupied regions, Beye noted that the UNITA leadership has
pledged to make new improvement on June 17 to 21.
</P>
<P>
Technical groups made up of representatives from various
parties will soon set for four sensitive areas including UNITA
headquarters in Bailundo and Andulo for observation and
inspection before the hand-over of authority to the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
