<HEADLINE> 91 Mortars, Howitzers Recovered from Philippine Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Coast Guard divers
recovered 91 pieces of rusty live mortars and howitzers from the
sea in the central part of the country, an officer said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Officer Fernando Carmona of the Philippine Cost Guard said the
sunk explosives were found in the muddy sea floor some 21 feet
deep near the port of Batangas city.
</P>
<P>
The mortars and howitzers were believed to be manufactured in
the United States some four to six years ago, Carmona said, adding
that the explosives would still blow up if not handled properly.
</P>
<P>
Port officials said the explosives contained in broken wooden
crates were part of illegal shipment of arms for the rebels or
criminal syndicates in the country.
</P>
<P>
They said the explosives, a number of which had been discovered
by fishermen in 1993, were believed thrown into the sea by
smugglers to avoid apprehension by authorities. 
