<HEADLINE> S. Korean Economy to Remain Sluggish in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean economy will remain
sluggish and unemployment will rise in the second half of this
year, Governor of the Bank of Korea Chon Chol-hwan said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Though the South Korean current account balance will continue
to show a surplus, its exports would not grow sustainingly in the
period, Chon said.
</P>
<P>
At same time, export conditions would not improve because of
the Japanese yen's devaluation, Chon added.
</P>
<P>
The yen tumbled to 139.33 against the U.S. dollar Monday, the
lowest in seven years, after a seven week slide which, it is
feared, will trigger a new crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor predicted that inflation will go on
rising because of an increase in the tax rate and public expenses.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the country's monetary policy will be
flexible to prevent contraction of the economy as much as
possible, and to support industrial and financial restructuring,
which is a condition tied to the rescue loan of 57 billion
U.S. dollars from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank would do its best to help small and
medium-size companies and the export industry by providing loans,
said the governor.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has been in a serious financial crisis with 155.2
billion U.S. dollars in foreign debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
