<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Near-Term Outlook for Australian Dollar Seen Grim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The near term outlook for the
Australian dollar is pretty grim with shaky financial markets in
Asia and soft commodity prices weighing on the unit, currency
analysts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said it was hard to ferret out anything positive for
the Australian dollar, with little evidence of support
materializing and the unit exploring the 61.00-U.S.-cent level.
</P>
<P>
There was no basis for the currency to stop there either, with
many expecting the local dollar to fall to 60.00 U.S. cents and
even lower.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar fell to its lowest point in almost 12
years Tuesday, hitting a new low of 61.10 U.S. cents, and it
recovered slightly to close at 61.23 U.S. cents from 62.02 U.S.
cents Monday.
</P>
<P>
The local currency is beset by two major factors, unsettled
financial markets in Asia which have contributed to a "sell the
Australian dollar as a proxy for the region mentality" and
worsening commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
"I really don't think you have to look much further than
Japan," Helen Camp, senior economist with Westpac Bank told the
Australian Associated Press Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, she noted that the instability in Russia, and the
implied threat to dump gold, aluminum and palladium have cast a
pall over commodity prices and been reflected in increased
pressure on the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Gold, a key barometer for the Australian dollar, has plunged to
trade around 288 U.S. dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
Other commodity prices offered no comfort Tuesday with nickel
prices in free fall on the London Metal Exchange Monday night,
hitting a 26-month low of 4,700 U.S. dollars a ton.
</P>
<P>
The Asian economic crisis has led to a crisis of confidence in
Australian business and its impact has been steadily undermining
the local economy and, in turn, the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
"It's a murky picture," said David Moore, an economist with the
Commonwealth Bank of Australia.
</P>
<P>
However, both he and Camp agreed that more evidence was needed
that Australia's economy would head for a slowdown in the second
half before there was further pressure on the Reserve Bank of
Australia to cut interest rates further.
</P>
<P>
Lower rates would weigh on the Australian dollar, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
"The domestic story is not the main negative for the Aussie
(dollar)," Camp said.
</P>
<P>
She said the foreign exchange market was unlikely to settle
down until the yen reached more comfortable levels and the
economic situation in Japan settled down, but she did not expect
that would happen overnight.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar is now at its lowest level since the
giddy days of late July 1986. It traded down to an intraday low of
57.17 U.S. cents on the 28th of that month and closed at 59.60
U.S. cents on the 31st of July, 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
