Holding important responsibilities for the peace, stability and
prosperity of the world in the 21st century, China and the United
States and their leaders must show great foresight and proceed
from the fundamental interests of their peoples, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Only thus can they do away with all kinds of disturbances and
obstacles, and develop the Sino-U.S. relationship continuously,
Jiang emphasized.
</P>
<P>
"I'm looking forward to meeting President Clinton in Beijing,
and his visit to China will undoubtedly promote the bilateral
relationship in a sound and stable direction," said the Chinese
president.
</P>
<P>
Berger told Jiang that Clinton values the development of the
bilateral relations and regards his upcoming visit to China as the
most important event in his second term of presidency, he said.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton is also confident that his visit will score
important and positive outcome, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen, Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan, and Liu Huaqiu, director of the State Council's Foreign
Affairs Office, also met with Berger earlier today.
</P>
<P>
Berger, who arrived here Monday afternoon as guest of the
Chinese Foreign Ministry, will leave Beijing late this evening,
winding up his China trip.
</P>
<P>
Berger visited China in August last year to prepare for
President Jiang's state visit to the U.S. last fall.  
</P>
</TEXT>
