<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets U.S. Security Assistant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Qian Qichen, in a
meeting today with Samuel Berger, assistant to the U.S. president
for national security affairs, said that President Clinton's
upcoming state visit to China is another important event in the
Sino-U.S. relationship since President Jiang Zemin's successful
U.S. trip last October.
</P>
<P>
As long as the two countries approach their relationship with a
view toward "wide-ranging and shared" interests and the 21st
century, joint efforts will certainly make President Clinton's
China visit a complete success, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that Berger's current visit to China is to prepare for
the presidential visit, to which the Chinese side attaches great
importance.
</P>
<P>
Berger said that he was delighted to have the opportunity to
meet with Qian again. He added that President Jiang Zemin's
successful visit to the U.S. last year has pushed forward the
bilateral relationship and has enabled the American people to gain
a better understanding of China and Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is here to lay groundwork for President
Clinton's visit to China, the first one paid by a U.S. president
in nearly a decade. He expressed the conviction that the visit
will help improve and develop bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Qian and Berger also exchanged views on the situation in South
Asia. Both believed that the international community must take
effective and feasible measures to halt nuclear arms race in the
region and prevent the nuclear weapons proliferation, in order to
restore and safeguard peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan met with and had a
working luncheon with Berger earlier today. 
