<HEADLINE> Australian Sharemarket Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket Tuesday
closed weaker but rallied off its morning lows in the afternoon
session on a futures-led recovery as investors sought oversold
stocks.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 18 points, or 0.67 percent,
lower at 2,671.1. It fell to a low of 2,637.2 in the morning
session, and peaked at 2,689.1 after the opening bell.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed down 12.1 points, or 1.11
percent, at 1,080.0 and the all industrials index closed down 26.4
points, or 0.56 percent, at 4,650.5.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 313.46 million shares valued at 1.06
billion Australian dollars (657.2 million U.S. dollars), with
falling stocks easily outnumbering rises by 766 to 366
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Data released Tuesday showed that the Asian currency crisis
fueled a massive 2 billion Australian dollars (1.22 billion U.S.
dollars) blowout in Australia's current account deficit in the
first three months of 1998, bringing it to a three-year high.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said that the current account deficit added to
investors' negative sentiment, but a rise on the Tokyo stock
exchange eased immediate concerns. The Nikkei 225 index closed 233
points higher at 15,554.
</P>
<P>
Topping volume was Telstra Corp with turnover of 14.31 million
receipts. The Telco giant's installment receipts closed down three
cents at 3.66.
</P>
<P>
Market heavyweight News Corp. gained 5.2 cents, off a low of
9.68 Australian dollars, and its preferred scrip gained five off a
low of 8.52.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 49.5 points, or 4.30 percent, to 1101.0,
with Normandy Mining losing six cents, or 4.14 percent, and Lihir
Gold losing nine, or 4.48 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Westpac Banking Corp. went ex-dividend, closing down
35.2, or 3.38 percent, National Australia Bank lost 19 cents,
Commonwealth Bank of Australia lost 13 and ANZ, which brokerage
firm Merrill Lynch said had strong earnings growth ahead, closed
down 16.1, or 1.44 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
