<HEADLINE> EU to Send Relief Supplies to Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission cleared on
Tuesday an emergency humanitarian aid worth 1.5 million Ecus (1.65
million U.S. dollars) for victims of last week's earthquake in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The aid, to be managed by the European Community Humanitarian
Office, will enable humanitarian organizations to carry out
immediate relief operations in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The EU funding will cover essentials for survival and medical
assistance.
</P>
<P>
The tremor, measuring 7.0 on the open-ended Richter scale, hit
northeast Afghanistan on May 30 and humanitarian organizations
that stayed in the area since the last quake estimated that up to
3,000 people may have died and as many people have been injured.
</P>
<P>
EU officials said that since the area is still difficult to
access due to heavy rains and flooding, it is hard to estimate the
exact casualties and damage caused by the quake.
</P>
<P>
The officials cited an initial estimate as describing that up
to 40 villages had been destroyed by the quake.
</P>
<P>
An earlier earthquake hit the same area this February and the
most affected areas are Rustaq, Chah Ab and Shahr-e-burg in
Afghanistan's Takhar and Badakhstan provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
