<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Working to Develop Climatological Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are working to
explore ways of untilizing climatological resources in northwest
China, which has long been plagued by sandstorms and dry spells,
according to researchers at the Lanzhou branch of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Developing wind and solar energy resources are key areas for
utilization of climatological resources. The solar energy reserve
in northwest China is only next to that in the Tibet Autonomous
Region, and most part of the region has over 3,000 hours of
sunshine each year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the region's wind resources also takes the lead in
the country, which covers nine parts including western Gansu,
northern Qinghai, and northwestern Xinjiang, covering an area of
155,000 sq km and with an installed power-generating capacity of
150 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
New energy research institutes and solar energy developing
corporations have been founded in Gansu Province and the Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Forestry depletion has slowed down since Gansu Province
introduced the use of solar-fueled cooking stove in mid arid
regions. A solar power supply demonstration region has been set up
in Xinjiang, and the region also has made great progress in
generating power through wind.
</P>
<P>
The wind power plant in Dabancheng, Xinjiang, has a total
installed capacity of 2,000 kilowatts, and generates six million
kwhs of electricity each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
