<HEADLINE> CD Members Condemn India, Pakistan Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Forty-six 61 members and observers
of the Conference on Disarmament (CD) on Tuesday signed a joint
statement, condemning nuclear tests by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The signatories "are alarmed and deeply concerned at nuclear
testing by India and Pakistan," said the statement, which was
drafted by Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"They condemn all nuclear testing and consider such acts to be
contrary to the international consensus which bans the testing of
nuclear weapons and other explosive devices," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The tests undertaken by India and Pakistan "blatantly undermine
the international regime of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons"
and "threaten and undermine the process of disarmament and the
goal of eliminating nuclear weapons altogether," it said.
</P>
<P>
The CD members and observers called on India and Pakistan to
resolve tensions between them "through constructive dialogue and
negotiation." 
</P>
