<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Strong protests by the opposition
have forced the Indian government to bring gas prices in the
country back to normal except for a 1-rupee increase as tax.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha announced the government move
at the on-going Lower House session here Tuesday in response to
the opposition parties' protests against the steep increase in the
gas price following the budget presentation Monday and demand for
its immediate withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Accusing Sinha of misleading the House, opposition members
contended that the prices have gone up by about 4 rupees per liter
of gas though he had announced imposition of a cess of 1 rupee per
liter for the development of roads.
</P>
<P>
The entire opposition staged a walkout after accusing the
government of being "irresponsible" with the budget and charging
the finance minister with not giving a satisfactory explanation to
them.
</P>
<P>
The announcement by the minister failed to pacify the
opposition which maintained that the government was speaking in
different voices.
</P>
<P>
Janet Al leader Jail Reedy said here Tuesday that never in the
history of independent India had such a thing occurred. 
</P>
