<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chittagong Stock Exchange Computerizes Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chittagong Stock Exchange (CSE)
in Bangladesh adopted an automated trading system Tuesday,
broadening its business horizon beyond Bangladesh's biggest port
city.
</P>
<P>
"The automated system will create a lot of confidence in the
country's capital market, not only among the locals but also the
foreign investors," CSE chief Khosru Mahmud Chowdhury said at a
ceremony held in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
After the opening-up of the country's capital market during the
first half of the 1990s, foreign investors put a substantial
amount in the emerging market.
</P>
<P>
But they deserted the market after a share scam in late 1996
which many felt was a result of the lack of transparency and
accountability in market activities.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors would feel encouraged to come back to
Bangladesh, because they want to see and invest in a transparent
capital market, Chowdhury said.
</P>
<P>
The automated trading system project is being implemented with
an 80-million-U.S.-dollar loan from the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
CSE stockbrokers from Dhaka and the northeastern city of Sylhet
as well as Chittagong will be able to place sell or buy orders on
the screens.
</P>
<P>
The system will be expanded to the country's northwestern and
southwestern cities of Bogra and Kulna later.
</P>
<P>
There are only two stock exchange centers, Chittagong and
Dhaka, in this South Asian country at present.
</P>
<P>
The CSE is the country's first to introduce a computerized
trading system and the Dhaka Stock Exchange is due to have its
automated trading system later this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
