<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Investment Fair Opens in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A 220-strong trade delegation
from the Chinese mainland started face-to-face contacts with
potential overseas investors at the 98 China (HK) Investment and
Trade Fair, which opened here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth and the largest ever investment and trade
fair organized by the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, composed of officials and entrepreneurs from 22
mainland provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions, brought
more than 700 investment projects to Hong Kong, a major source of
overseas investment in the mainland, An Min, assistant minister of
MOFTEC, said here Tuesday at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
A large number of participants in this year's fair are from
China's central and western parts, which are less developed than
the country's booming coastal regions but abundant in labor and
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
"We are making efforts to attract more and more overseas
business people to invest in the vast hinterland," the assistant
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 738 projects available at the fair, a large proportion
are related to agriculture, infrastructure and hi-tech industry,
the fields which the Chinese government has encouraged overseas
investors to pour money into.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the first quarter of 1998, China had approved
more than 300,000 overseas-funded ventures and half of them have
gone into operation, statistics provided by the MOFTEC showed.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, the country has actually made use of
foreign direct investment exceeding 230 billion U.S. dollars and
Hong Kong accounted for 54 percent of the total, topping the list
of overseas investors in China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
As part of the fair, a half-day seminar was held here Tuesday
to provide a forum for high-ranking Chinese officials to brief the
Hong Kong business community on the latest investment environment
and policies in the mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
