<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Conducts Public Consultation on Transport Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government Tuesday
released a consultation document on the Third Comprehensive
Transport Study (CTS-3) to invite public views on how Hong Kong
will be best served by its transport policies for the next two
decades.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said the projected population growth, an
enhanced housing development program and the increasing
cross-boundary traffic with China's mainland have pointed to a
need to update and refine Hong Kong's transport infrastructure and
policy framework.
</P>
<P>
"To this end, the government commissioned the CTS-3 in August
1997 to study our future transport needs," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
This will provide the broad parameters for the long-term
development of Hong Kong's transport infrastructure, for the
expansion of public transport services and for setting the traffic
management objectives for the future, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Initial tests are being conducted as part of the CTS-3," the
spokesman said. "We consider it useful to have public views on the
major initiatives being examined in the study so that these could
be incorporated in the detailed recommendations before they are
finalized in early 1999," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Public views are sought on matters such as providing transport
infrastructure in a more timely manner to meet anticipated
demands; according priority to railways, which are the most
efficient mass carriers, in the use of valuable land space; better
coordination of the services of various public transport modes;
rationalizing traffic demand and managing it in more
cost-effective ways through the application of new technologies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
