<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Stock Market Brisk in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's stock market reported a
brisk business in the first quarter of this year, compared with
the last quarter of 1997, the Business Concord reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Nigerian Stock Exchange in Lagos recorded
a turnover of 389.9 million shares worth of 2.7 billion Naira
(about 90 Naira equals to one U.S. Dollar) in the first three
months.
</P>
<P>
This, it said, represents an increase of 25.8 percent and 11.7
percent, respectively, over the level of the preceding quarter.
</P>
<P>
The story will be different, however, if compared with the
first quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The total shares changing hands in the period decreased by 5.8
percent, while the total value of securities traded in the
Exchange was down by 1.3 percent, due to losses in equity prices
and the delisting of two distressed banks.
</P>
<P>
The All-Share Index closed at 6,298.5, down by 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in Nigeria's stock market increased by 57.7
percent in the first quarter over the same period of 1997 to
reach 4.1 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
After consultations with dealing members, the Exchange in the
first quarter began the implementation of its Automated Trading
System, in an effort to make its service more efficient and
cost-effective.
</P>
<P>
The performance of the market in the rest time of the year
depends on the government's determination to go on with the
proposed privatization program and its capability to address the
lingering problem of irregular fuel and power supply, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
