<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis' impact on Kenyan Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Asian financial crisis has had
some effect on the local market of the Nairobi Stock Exchange
(NSE) as the market is driven by local forces, according to the
NSE boss.
</P>
<P>
The Asian crisis "impacted some fear in some major investors"
because NSE is not international, NSE's Chief Executive Job
Kihumba told the national daily Kenya Times last week.
</P>
<P>
Beginning from August last year, Kihumba said, foreign firms'
performance went down due to the impasse between Kenya and the
World Bank and the tense political climate before the General
Election held last December.
</P>
<P>
However, foreigners brought in 31 million U.S. Dollars to buy
shares floated by the Kenya Commercial Bank, he noted, adding
that these interests of foreigners indicated that their
suspicions about Kenya have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The total value of shares traded at NSE stood at 6.1 billion
Kenyan Shillings (about 100 million U.S. Dollars) last year,
compared with 3.9 billion Shillings (about 65 million U.S.
Dollars) in 1996, according to Kihumba.
</P>
<P>
In bonds, the total value traded at NSE last year recorded 15
billion Shillings (about 250 million U.S. Dollars) with the
National Bank of Kenya traded bonds standing at 10 billion
Shillings (about 170 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The number of traded transactions was 80,000 contracts last
year, compared to 60,000 contracts traded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that by mid 1999, the NSE performance will be
better as "we should have started to see positive signs of
economic development."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the future of the NSE will, more or less, depend
on the performance of the country's economy because companies
listed at NSE represent all sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The NSE boss pointed out that one of the biggest bottlenecks
in Kenya's economic development is the government expenditure
which has denied other sectors of the economy development
capital.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, the Kenyan government has for the first time
acknowledged that it must reduce its expenditure, adding that if
the government pursued its cost reduction policy, it would end up
with surpluses to channel into other sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
In his view, NSE has become an important player in Kenya's
economy since the liberalization process was launched by the
government several years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
