<HEADLINE> Nigeria Accuses U.S., Ghana, S. Africa of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has accused
the U.S., Ghana and South Africa of collaborating to destabilize
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Alahji Wada Nas, Special Adviser to Head of State General Sani
Abacha, made the allegation at a press conference held Monday in
the Federal Capital Territory Abuja.
</P>
<P>
"We are fully aware of the collaboration between some
countries, namely America, South Africa and Ghana, with some
human rights and pro-democracy groups to destabilize Nigeria,"
Nas said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, an American group in Ghana organized a
meeting for that objective from May 6 to May 8 at Achimota Hotel
in Northern Ghana.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the Ghanaian government may not have
been aware of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Nas alleged that the meeting was attended by no fewer than 14
human rights and pro-democracy groups. "The meeting was organized
by America, while the trainers were from South Africa and Ghana
was the host," he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting adopted the strategy of defiance campaign, mass
protests, boycott rallies and intensive social mobilization to
destabilize the Abacha government, he said.
</P>
<P>
The special adviser alleged that at the end of the meeting,
each participant was promised a grant of 50,000 U.S. Dollars for
their activities between June and July.
</P>
<P>
Nas also accused the European Union of providing 250,000 U.S.
Dollars to a pro-democracy group known as the United Action for
Democracy (UAD). The money, he said, is to subvert any
pro-government activities and organize mass protests between June
and August.
</P>
<P>
He alleged that a group known as the Joint Action Committee of
Nigeria has planned to stage neighborhood rallies all over the
country on June 12.
</P>
<P>
The special adviser said the country's law enforcement
agencies have the full capability to maintain the law and called
on Nigerian people to shun all unpatriotic actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
