<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Tumbles to its Lowest Point in 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar tumbled to
its lowest point in almost 12 years Tuesday after the Australian
Bureau of Statistics reported a 2.0 billion Australian dollars
(1.22 billion U.S. dollars) blowout in the nation's current
account deficit.
</P>
<P>
A sinking Japanese yen also placed pressure on the battered
unit, which plunged almost one U.S. cent to its new low of 61.10
U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
After heading towards the 61.00 level, the currency recovered
slightly to close at 61.23 from 62.02 Monday.
</P>
<P>
St George Bank Manager of Foreign Exchange Trading Stuart Moore
said the unit could be expected to fall further in the short term.
</P>
<P>
A rampaging U.S. dollar/Japanese yen exchange rate and a soft
gold price was combining with the Asian economic crisis to provide
a worrying time for the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Moore said as the Japanese currency marched towards 140.00
against the U.S. dollar, market participants would be on the
look-out for intervention from the Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Closer to home was the possibility the Reserve Bank of
Australia (RBA) would jump into the market to defend the
Australian dollar if it dipped below 61 U.S. cents, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
The currency is now below levels that prompted RBA intervention
only a few weeks ago when the unit touched 61.69 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The RBA intervention in May was credited to a disorderly fall
in the Australian dollar and Moore pointed out that at present the
local currency was conducting a fairly orderly drop.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended the day here at 85.33 from 86.20
against Japanese yen and at 1.0906 from 1.1022 against German
mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
