<HEADLINE> Heavy rains Eases Drought in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rains in the past 12 days have
eased the severe drought in most part of Vietnam, the Vietnam News
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The highest-recorded rainfall was 158 mm last week in the
catchment of the Da River which feeds Hoa Binh Reservoir in Lai
Chau province, 300 kilometers north-west of Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
The Central Weather Bureau is forecasting more heavy rains for
later this week.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily also said that heavy rains filled up
reservoirs at major hidro-electricity plants but raised the danger
of flash floods in mountainous regions.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City in the south was hit hard by whirlwinds with
torrential rain last week.
</P>
<P>
Strong winds uprooted trees and swept away make-shift
iron-sheet roofing in the city.
</P>
<P>
Officials have warned coastal farmers to prepare for floods
caused by high tides in the south. 
</P>
