<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Capital Encouraged in Guangzhou's State Sector Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- This capital city of south
China's Guangdong Province is intensifying efforts to use overseas
capital in the reform of state-run small and medium-sized
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The latest effort was a property rights transfer fair held in
Hong Kong recently, organized by the city government, said Liang
Zhengxiang, deputy director of the government's information
office, who attended the fair.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou prepared nearly 100 projects in the sectors of
chemicals, metallurgy, machinery and electronics, foodstuffs,
textiles, hardwares, and building materials. More than 350 Hong
Kong entrepreneurs attended the fair and signed some agreements.
</P>
<P>
The city worked out favorable policies to encourage overseas
participation in the reform of its small and medium-sized state
businesses. The historical debts of an enterprise, for example,
can be deducted from reassessed property values.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors are also encouraged to run service
businesses at their Chinese partners' old factory sites, or to
transform related enterprises elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Overseas involvement can take forms like purchasing,
acquisition, leasing or contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
