<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jilin Conducts Auditing of State-Owned Grain Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Jilin province
has been conducting auditing of the financial affairs of
state-owned grain companies in the province since mid-March in a
bid to find out the real causes for the companies' losses and to
work out countermeasures.
</P>
<P>
Auditors have so far successfully prevented more than 30
million yuan from possible losses by screening their operations
and financial accounts, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
Jilin, a well-known maize producer, has 1,445 state-owned grain
companies. Some of them have been suffering from economic losses
for years. The auditing operation will be completed by late June.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that state grain companies in China
have lost more than 100 billion yuan in the past seven years due
to bad performances and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji stressed the
inevitability and urgency to restructure the nation's grain
marketing system.
</P>
<P>
And the reform will be carried out in line with the principles
of cutting administrative functions from State-owned grain
companies, separating storage from management, central from local
responsibilities and new from old accounts, as well as improving
the pricing system for the grain market, according to earlier
reports.
</P>
<P>
The main problems in China's grain marketing system lie in the
fact that the state-owned grain companies play a dual role of both
storage and marketing, with a managerial mechanism that has failed
to operate in line with the laws governing market operation and
has resulted in severe financial losses.
</P>
<P>
For decades, China's grain firms have mixed government
functions and commercial roles, with the result that they have
been suffering from bad debts and financial losses for many years.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the state grain firms are trapped by planned
economic structures; they do not have the authority to make
managerial decisions on their own, and suffer from overstaffing,
high operation costs and poor economic returns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
