<HEADLINE> Iran's MPs Question FM over Americans' Visits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Majlis (Parliament) members
have asked Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi for explanation over
the recent trips to Iran by several Americans, Jomhuri Islami
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Majlis members asked why the Foreign Ministry granted entry
visas to American citizens, political and security elements,
especially to Rupert Murdoch, "one of the main pillars of Zionism
and ringleaders of cultural invasion in the world."
</P>
<P>
They accused Murdoch of visiting various Iranian cities in
order to assess Iran's atmosphere to stage his cultural assault,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi is not available for comment at least for now.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of the conservative Guardians Council Ayatollah Ahmad
Jannati on Friday also accused the Foreign Ministry of inviting
American and Israeli elements to visit the country.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry rejected the accusation Saturday, terming
Jannati's remarks as a "slip of the tongue."
</P>
<P>
Up to now, no Israeli individual has been granted visa and nor
will they be granted visa in the future, the Foreign Ministry
said, adding that they have no plans to issue visas to
U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
Former Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati Tuesday was quoted
as saying that Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei was
"determined" that Iran would not resume relations with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The recent visits by some American citizens to Iran had
nothing to do with Iran's principled policy towards the U.S., said
Velayati, who is Khamanei's advisor on foreign affairs. 
