<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Improve Laws for Intellectual Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China plans to revise some laws
concerning the protection of the intellectual property rights, in
a bid to further improve the country's law system in the field,
according to a latest report from the State Intellectual Property
Office (SIPO).
</P>
<P>
The SIPO will join the scheduled boost for revising Patent
Law. The work has been listed into the legislative agenda of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
The would-be law revision aims to address the new issues which
occur in the market economy, the SIPO, the top official organ
which leads China's endeavor to protect domestic and overseas
intellectual property rights, said in its long-range development
program.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the revised Patent Law should benefit the
newly-developed fields, such as microelectronic technology,
software engineering, data base and biological engineering, the
program said.
</P>
<P>
The revision draft of Law on Copyright will be deliberated by
the NPC Standing Committee around the end of the year, said Xu
Yulin, a senior official with the Legislative Affairs Office of
the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the country will draft a new law to protect
business secrets for enterprises and individuals, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
"We must strengthen the legislation and law enforcement for IPR
protection," he said.
</P>
<P>
The SIPO also plans to receive 100,000 patent applications
annually around the year 2000. And the annual applications around
2010 will reach 150,000.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the SIPO will further boost the patent work in
enterprises, research institutes and higher-educational
institutes. But some related statistics showed that China's
research and higher-learning institutes lack the awareness of IPR
protection.
</P>
<P>
The nation has adopted trademark, patent and copyright laws as
well as regulations on the protection of computer software and the
law against unfair competition since 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
