<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minorities Benefit From Foreign Capital (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Uygur farmer Abli Memet never
expected that his family's poor living conditions could be
improved so greatly a year ago when he put up an iron plate -- the
sign for involving in a UNDP project -- on his door.
</P>
<P>
In mid-May of this year, however, Trine M. Lund-Jensen, UNDP
assistant resident representative to China, visited Abli's home
and spoke highly of his pioneering effort in improving his living
and production conditions.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old Uygur got a 1,000-yuan low-interest loan from
the local UNDP project office last year, and used 600 yuan to buy
a timber processing machine, and 400 yuan for two lambs. Now, he
earns 15 yuan every day by processing timber, and has three heads
of sheep which his wife takes care of.
</P>
<P>
The farmer with only three years of schooling has learned to
make money by doing business, and more important, he has come to
know how to develop contacts with financial institutions through
signing contracts and paying off loans in installments, a local
economist said. But years ago, he never tried to invest his money
in production when offered subsidies for poverty relief.
</P>
<P>
Some remote areas in China, where ethnic minorities live in
compact communities, are economically underdeveloped due to
different causes, including limited traffic means. Few local
Uygurs have an awareness of a market economy due to the lack of
education, Ms Trine said.
</P>
<P>
"So, we are planning some poverty relief projects to help
improve their ability in doing business and managing money
matters," she explained.
</P>
<P>
UNDP started poverty eradication projects in China in 1994, and
has opened projects in 48 counties of 11 provinces and autonomous
regions, involving 87,000 households of 420,000 farmers, mostly
ethnic minorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minorities Benefit From Foreign Capital (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Last year, the organization offered Xinjiang 1.8 million US
dollars in free aid, and the regional government was to provide
another 82 million yuan for the effort.
</P>
<P>
Local project offices charge very low interests of the loans in
a bid to teach farmers to do business in the process, Ms Trine
said.
</P>
<P>
Farmers receive free technical training before they are granted
such loans, and then they buy means of agricultural production
under the guidance of village and township officials.
</P>
<P>
In Abli's hometown of Hotan prefecture, 63,000 rural families
have the iron plate on their doors. In 1996, their per-capita
income was less than 600 yuan, but last year, half the families'
income rose to 650 to 700 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Hotan, on the southern edge of the Taklimakan Desert, the
world's second largest, is one of the country's most impoverished
areas, and local Uygur farmers know very little about the outside
world. But things are changing.
</P>
<P>
Not knowing a single written character, Abli learned to
understand what UNDP stands for. "The United Nations, linking up
all countries, is the right place to help solve various problems
of different ethnic groups," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The unique management methods adopted in implementing the
poverty relief projects have breathed new air into local efforts
to help the needy, and participating households have also set a
good example to others," said Fang Xinmin, a local official in
charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture plans to use government supporting funds to
expand the poverty relief practice to more areas.
</P>
<P>
China also uses capital from other international financial
organizations and governments to speed up its poverty relief
process.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank began in 1995 to join in China's nationwide
campaign to fight poverty. And by last year, it launched or
planned to launch poverty relief projects in 94 state-designated
poor counties, aiming to provide sufficient food and clothing for
8 million people, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
