<HEADLINE> 5 Ministers Sacked in Congolese Cabinet Shake-up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Democratic Congolese President
Laurent Kabila sacked five ministers under probe for alleged
corruption and brought in 13 new ministers in a major cabinet
shake-up Monday, a report reaching here Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo read the new government list
on state television on behalf of President Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Ministers who have been detained pending inquiries into the
financial management of their ministries have all been fired,
Kongolo noted.
</P>
<P>
The ministers dropped include Planning Minister Etienne
Richard Mbaya, Energy Minister Lokombe Kitete, Information
Minister and Public Enterprises Minister Kambale Mututulo.
</P>
<P>
Among the 13 new ministers is Deogratias Bugera, former
Secretary-General of Kabila's Alliance of Democratic Forces for
the Liberation of Congo whose forces helped topple Mobutu Sese
Seko. He becomes Minister of State in Charge of the Presidency.
</P>
<P>
All of the five sacked ministers are being questioned as part
of the probe into the allegations. They were taken in for
questioning since last weekend in relation to the management of
funds handled by their ministries, presidency sources said
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The directors of the state electricity, water and oil
companies were also being detained, one source added.
</P>
<P>
Kabila declared war on corruption shortly after taking power
in May 1997 following a seven-month war which toppled Mobutu who
had ruled the central African country for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Kabila has time and again warned his officials
that those abusing their positions for personal gain would be
punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
