<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Diversion Project Doing Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China's project of diverting water
from the Yellow River, the second longest in the country, has been
proved to be a successful case in using loans from the World Bank,
a senior World Bank official said after a recent inspection tour
of the Wanjiazhai Water Control Project.
</P>
<P>
The bank is expected to grant loans to the second phase of the
Wanjiazhai project, part of the Yellow River diversion scheme, as
the bank was satisfied with the performance of loan management for
the first phase, said Daniel Gunarat Nam, chief resident expert of
the World Bank in China.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the Wanjiazhai Water Control Project, in
north China's Shanxi Province, is to diver water from the Yellow
River to Taiyuan, the provincial capital. It has cost an
investment of 12 billion yuan, of which 400 million U.S. dollars
were provided by the World Bank. The second phase will extend the
water channel from Taiyuan to Datong and Shuozhou.
</P>
<P>
During the tour, World Bank officials inspected project
progress, financial control, contract management, environmental
protection, arrangement of resettlers, performance of contractors
and other aspects in relation with the project.
</P>
<P>
They said the tripartite management mechanism of the project is
scientific and its practice of having unified management of
surface and underground water should be popularized in other parts
of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
