<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Builds Nation-wide GPS Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China's first national
high-accuracy global positioning system (GPS) network passed
assessment recently.
</P>
<P>
This marked major progress in the country's GPS application.
</P>
<P>
The nation-wide network has an error rate of one cm for every
1,000 km. It consists of five national satellite tracking
stations, 30 provincial level stations and 800 regional stations.
</P>
<P>
Wang Quan, director of the Modern Earth Surveying Institute
under the Chinese Academy of Surveying and Mapping, said that the
network can provide prompt and timely geographical information
about the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The GPS is an international electronic tracking system that is
supported by 24 satellites around the earth.
</P>
<P>
Feng Haiqing, general manager of the General Integrated
Technology Company under the China Great Wall Computer Group, said
that since GPS entered China at the beginning of the 1990s, China
has made big progress in research and application of the
technology.
</P>
<P>
The number of Chinese manufacturers of GPS equipment has
increased from few dozen to over 150.
</P>
<P>
The country has already used GPS technology in the fields of
aviation, surveying, telecommunications, transport, banking,
public security, fire fighting, emergency aid, exploration,
automobiles and defense.
</P>
<P>
A 150-million-yuan national priority project of earthquake
monitoring is under construction. The project is based on GPS
technology. It monitors the movement of earth plates around and
inside China so as to provide accurate evidence for medium- and
long-term earthquake forecast.
</P>
<P>
Li Yanxing, an official from the State Seismological Bureau,
said that the bureau conducted monitoring survey through a
regional GPS network around Beijing in the two consecutive years
of 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Results of the survey showed that earthquake activities in the
region were on the rise, which has been proved by earthquakes in
Hebei, Tangshan and Beijing recently.
</P>
<P>
Steve Smith, business development manager of Trimble Navigation
New Zealand Ltd., is among the foreign business persons attending
the China International Exhibition on GPS Equipment and
Application Technology that opened here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chinese manufacturers can produce all kinds of GPS
equipment now. However, he points out that China is yet to develop
multi-frequency chips that will increase the accuracy of such
equipment by thousands of times.
</P>
<P>
He believes that China is yet to tap the huge potential market
of GPS application. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Studies of Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau Should Be Strengthened: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An academician from the Chinese
Academy of Sciences has called on researchers to pay more
attention to the studies of the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau, the
world's roof.
</P>
<P>
"The evolution and existence of the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau has
a great influence on the natural environment in Asia and even the
earth, and researches on global changes will come nowhere if not
considering this fact," Li Jijun, a professor of geography
from the Lanzhou University, said at a seminar here today.
</P>
<P>
"The studies of the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau will help us better
understand our ecological conditions and solve the current
environmental problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, studies in this regard has come to be a
hot-point for geo-scientists since the early 1980s, and
significant achievements are now expected.
</P>
<P>
However, the academician said, there is still a long way to
cover in order to reach the real truth.
</P>
<P>
"We have found close interconnections between the rising of the
Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau and the environmental evolution in China
and east Asia," Li said, adding that the Yangtze and Yellow
rivers, China's two longest rivers, were formed during the
process of the plateau's rising.
</P>
<P>
"China's western part would not be so dry, the east would not be
so wet, and the current farmland in the lower reaches of the
Yangtze River and south China would be deserts, if there were not
the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Draft More Accurate Strata Chronological Table </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are drafting a
chronological table that is expected to accurately tell the
geological age of earth strata.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and
Paleoanthropology attached to the Chinese Academy of Sciences have
started to make the world's first chronological table of
biological strata and magnetic strata.
</P>
<P>
Huang Xueshi and his colleagues are collecting biological
stratum samples in the Yuanqu Basin at the northern bank in north
China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Geologists said there has been so far not any authoritative
chronological table to determine the age of a stratum in research
of ancient biology and and history of geology.
</P>
<P>
They said researchers used to calculate the geological age of a
stratum based on fossils of organisms buried at the same place and
other chemical characteristics, adding the method often leads to
big errors.
</P>
<P>
U.S. scientists have been applying ancient geomagnetism in the
determination of the geological age of a stratum. However, the
method lacks fossil samples to support the calculation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists are combining the two methods to draft a
more accurate chronological table.
</P>
<P>
Yuanqu Basin is rich in fossils of ancient organisms and
clearly divided geological layers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
