<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Laid-off Workers Apt to Have More Job Opportunities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- To Tang Feng, a laid-off worker from
a match factory in Jinan, capital city of east China's Shandong
Province, a career began at his 40s, when he went to settle in
Dajie Village, some 40 km from the city, to open a fish ground.
</P>
<P>
"Compared with local farmers, I'm advantageous to have market
information and expertise in fish breeding," said Tang, who
became confident after his half-year effort has transformed 40
ha. of waste waterlogged depression into 15 fish ponds where he
breeds salmon and soft-shelled turtles.
</P>
<P>
Dajie villagers have extended a welcome to Tang, saying that he
has made use of the idle land and spurring on local breeding
undertakings.
</P>
<P>
Recently, a mounting number of laid-off workers like Tang are
capitalizing on their chances in land exploration for cultivating
cash crops, vegetable and flowers of high economic value.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Taiyuan, capital of north China's Shanxi
Province, the land-use right of a third of the waste land that
went through auctions held in recent years has been purchased by
laid-off workers. And at a recent auction for waste land-use right
around the city, 70 percent of the participators are factory
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
China's rural area shows a low per-capita share of arable land,
according to economists. And it is encouraging to see the inflow
of laid-off workers engaging in the exploitation of waste
mountainsides, polders and ponds.
</P>
<P>
The laid-off workers rushing to the rural sector have come
mainly from mid-sized and small cities, an official from the labor
department in Shandong Province said. Compared with those from
large cities, they have more advantages in doing farming related
jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
