<HEADLINE> Israel, Jordan to Set Up Joint Industrial Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel and Jordan have agreed to
establish a joint industrial park along the border of the two
countries, local daily The Jerusalem Post reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that details of the park were finalized over
the weekend during a meeting between Israeli National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon and Jordanian Water and
Irrigation Minister Munther Haddadin, who is responsible for
joint projects with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will raise 280 million U.S. dollars for the
park, which will be located on both sides of the Jordan River.
</P>
<P>
The park will be a free-trade zone with a land area of 2,500
dunam (about 614 acres).
</P>
<P>
The two countries, which signed a peace treaty in 1994, are
also discussing a number of other joint projects, such as a canal
between the Dead Sea and Red Sea. 
</P>
