<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Temple Rebuilding Marks Noted Monk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A rebuilding project has started in
the Yuhua Temple of Tongchuan city in northwest China's Shaanxi
province, where Monk Xuan Zang delivered sermons 1,300 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Xuan Zang is also the hero of a Chinese classic novel,
"Pilgrimage To The West", which is widely read across the country.
</P>
<P>
Located in the Yuhua Mountain of the Tongchuan City, the temple
used to be a temporary palace for Emperor Li Shimin's father of
the Tang Dynasty (618-907). It was turned into a temple in 651.
</P>
<P>
Master Xuan Zang, who was also a noted translator and traveler,
spent last four years of his life in the temple and died there in
664.
</P>
<P>
The rebuilding is expected to cost eight million yuan, and the
future temple will cover nearly two hectares and include main
halls, meditation rooms, corridors, a rostrum and a memorial
archway.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese Buddhist Association, once the project
is completed, a Buddhist theological institute and a charity
hospital are to be set up there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
