<HEADLINE> 25 ADF Rebels Killed in Joint Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-five rebels of the Allied
Democratic Forces (ADF) were killed last week in a joint army
operation launched by Uganda and the Democratic Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
They were killed when fleeing the ambush which occurred some
30 kms inside the Congo border, military sources were quoted by
Tuesday's New Vision daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources said: "following the hot pursuit by the two
friendly armies in the eastern Congo, Rwenzori mountains, some of
the ADF rebels are trying to cross to Ugandan border districts of
Kasese and Bundibugyo."
</P>
<P>
With the mounting pressure from the army, the heavily battered
rebels could no longer recruit, regroup or establish new
operation camps, they said.
</P>
<P>
To deny the rebels the opportunity to train some of their
victims, the two armies would meet every Friday to flush out and
wipe out the rebels and their remnants.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the joint efforts against the rebels, Nassur
Kibirige, the spokesman of the army second division stationed
along the western border, said: "we need each other in this
struggle to end this insurgency in western Uganda."
</P>
<P>
The border security pact signed between the two governments in
late April made these joint operations possible.
</P>
<P>
The western border areas are fields frequently haunted by the
ADF rebels and the remnants of the army of the former Zaire
regime. They looted villages and butched unarmed civilians,
posing a threat not only to these two countries but to their
neighbors as well.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to restore peace and rehabilitate the economy in
the northern and western districts, Ugandan President Y. Museveni
has ordered a reinforced military presence in the areas, forcing
the rebels to have a showdown with the army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
