<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mir's Orientation Restored, Gyrodynes Still Not Functioning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The alignment of Russia's Mir space
station has been fully restored and its scheduled docking with the
U.S. space shuttle Discovery is expected to go ahead as planned,
Itar-Tass reported early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"No obstacles to the orbital station Mir's mooring with the
U.S. spacecraft Discovery now exist," a duty operator with the
Mission Control said.
</P>
<P>
However, the alignment was sustained by Mir's engines rather
than the gyrodynes that automatically keep the space station
oriented to the sun to ensure that the solar panels generate the
maximum amount of energy.
</P>
<P>
The gyrodynes stopped functioning following the crash of Mir's
main computer late Saturday. A new computer has been replaced but
ground experts and the orbiter's crew are still struggling to
revitalize the gyrodynes, which do not need fuel to operate.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. space shuttle Discovery is due to take off at 22:00
GMT Tuesday from Cape Canaveral, Florida, for her last docking
with the aging Mir.
</P>
<P>
It will bring home Andrew Thomas, the NASA astronaut who
started his space journey in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
