<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Unveils Anti-Tobacco Advertisements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 1 (Xinhua) -- "Medical researchers believe
cigarettes are a leading cause of impotence," an advertisement
said. "Cigarettes. Still think they are sexy?"
</P>
<P>
This is one of the new anti-tobacco advertisements that radio
and TV stations begin airing next Monday throughout California.
</P>
<P>
Another advertisement features a man whose attempt to flirt
with a woman at a formal gala goes awry when the cigarette in his
mouth suddenly goes limp.
</P>
<P>
Such advertisements are aimed at getting through to a tough
audience, said Kim Belshe, director of the California Department
of Health Services, who believes American men care more for sex
than for health.
</P>
<P>
The concern over sex, not health, may get more men to stop
smoking, he added.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Christopher P. Evans of the University of California
pointed to the fact that, in a Massachusetts study conducted in
1994, scientists discovered that smokers are twice as likely to be
impotent as nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
The new anti-tobacco advertisements are part of a three-year,
67.5-million-dollar campaign in California, which has the nation's
second-lowest prevalence of adult smoking -- 18.2 percent --
behind Utah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
