<HEADLINE> Students Demonstrators Turn Violent in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's several hundred students
demonstrating in Harare to press the government to hike their
payout increments have turned violent and destroyed property
worth thousands of U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman confirmed the Monday incident and said that
no arrests had been made by late Monday afternoon, the Herald
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Trouble started when the students failed to see Minister of
Higher Education and Technology Ignatius Chombo, after having
gathered at the offices for the better part of Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
After being told by ministry officials that Chombo was not
available, the students started singing revolutionary songs and
scolding government officials.
</P>
<P>
The students started pelting the police with sticks and
stones. The police then forced the students to disperse only to
reappear in small groups within the city.
</P>
<P>
The students regrouped and allegedly started destroying
property.
</P>
<P>
Several offices, including the Herald House, were stoned.
Shops along Jason Moyo Avenue at central city and several cars
were also damaged. The Chicken Inn at Construction House was
severely damaged and food was looted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry of higher education and technology has
advised students, who have been in the streets in Harare, that
their petition has been handed over to Chombo. 
</P>
