<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Cotton Grower Successful in High-yield Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Remarkable results on the research
of high-yield cotton strains have been reported in the Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, China's leading cotton grower.
</P>
<P>
The research program, initiated in 1995, is aimed at bringing
the cotton output of Xinjiang to 1.5 billion kilograms and raising
the country's total cotton output by 500 million kilograms in the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Through the research, Xinjiang agro-scientists have developed
two ne cotton strains highly resistant to blight which are
suitable for either growing in southern and northern Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
Also as part of the efforts, the region has grown 760,000
hectares of cotton under wide-plastic sheeting, raising the per mu
(15 mu equals to one hectare) output to between 120 to 150
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The scientists have also sorted out ten high-yield,
fine-quality, and anti-decease varieties and two strains for
machine-picking. These fine breeds are expected to be widely
planted in other regions in northwest China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
