<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Financial Crisis Hurts California Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Asian financial crisis is
taking a toll on southern California's 30 billion dollar tourism
industry, according to industry sources.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, only 400 out of 4,500 Indonesians who booked
vacations through American Vacations Inc. made the trip to the
United States, Ritwan Mursalim, marketing manager for American
Vacations, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
"We never expected this to happen," said Mursalim, adding that
"We'll have to find a way to survive."
</P>
<P>
Japan Travel Bureau, the largest seller of U.S. tours from
Asia, saw that 20 percent of its bookings to Los Angeles canceled
from October through January, said Frank Murakami, who heads the
firm's Los Angeles office.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese account for about one in every four travel dollars
spent by foreigners in California, according to Jack Kyser, chief
economist at Los Angeles County Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
"You are losing some big spenders and that will take the cream
off the market," Kyser said, adding that those who do visit may be
staying in cheaper hotels than in the past.
</P>
<P>
Many tourist-related businesses are struggling to cope.
</P>
<P>
Big hotels near Disneyland are reporting fewer bookings from
Asia, which means fewer people visiting Disneyland theme park
either.
</P>
<P>
Retailers from South Coast Plaza in Costa Mesa to Rodeo Drive
in Beverly Hills are seeing a slump in sales as the number of
big-spending Japanese tourists tails off.
</P>
<P>
Nearly a year of economic chaos has created the worst
conditions in Asia in at least three decades, said some industry
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
They believe businesses that depend on Asian travelers could
see a downturn of 20 percent or more this year and could still be
feeling a pinch into the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
