<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Minister Slammed Public, Courts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Minister of Home Affairs
Dumiso Dabengwa has slammed the public, human rights activists,
and the courts for taking sides with college students following
the degeneration of Monday's demonstration into vandalism.
</P>
<P>
The minister took a swipe at the students and blamed them for
having an agenda of their own and playing to the tune of
"sponsors of violence and destabilization", the Herald reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of unruly students from Harare Polytechnic, Harare
Institute of Technology and the University of Zimbabwe have
participated in the demonstration organized by the Zimbabwe
National Students' Union, ending the relatively peaceful two-day
period and causing havoc in the city center.
</P>
<P>
Dabengwa said that police had always been uncomfortable with
student demonstrations in the city center and had only bowed down
due to pressure from both the public and the courts.
</P>
<P>
"Police have felt very uneasy about student behavior and hence
stopped them from marching into the city center," the minister
said, adding that "whenever violence erupted, police have been
blamed for igniting violence.''
</P>
<P>
"Yesterday, police monitored the situation from a distance and
did not use tear gas. The students have made their point. They
want their allowances reviewed," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"And for them to embark on unprovoked violence illustrates
that they have other motives other than having their point
heard," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dabengwa added that the students had gone to the extent of
wanting to burn the national flag and had to be stopped from
doing so by police.
</P>
<P>
The students staged the two-day demonstrations in Harare to
press the ministry of higher education and technology to increase
their pay-out increments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
