<HEADLINE> Tianjin to Establish "Nature Museum" at Bank of Bohai Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- North China's coastal city of
Tianjin is to establish an ancient coast and wetland "nature
museum" to exhibit wonders of ocean and land changes in the past
10,000 years.
</P>
<P>
The open museum is to be built in the 100-hectare Tianjin
nature reserve of coastal shell dyke.
</P>
<P>
The "exhibits" include four dykes formed by shells dating back
to 4,000 to 500 years ago, a ship built in Northern Song Dynasty
(960-1127 A.D.) and ancient tombs discovered on the dyke as well
as oyster reef with 2,000 to 6,000 years history.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a piece of unique primary wetland will also be
open to tourists.
</P>
<P>
Built in 1991, the shell dyke nature reserve has rich animal
and plant resources. More than a dozen species of mammals, over
100 species of birds, 60 kinds of fish and 12 varieties of aquatic
plants or plants in wetlands are residing in the area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
