<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls, Jazz to Fight again in NBA Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Chicago Bulls and the Utah
Jazz will open their rematch in the NBA Finals at the Delta Center
of Salt Lake City on Wednesday night, with Michael Jordan and the
Bulls vying for their sixth title and Karl Malone and John
Stockton looking for their first.
</P>
<P>
The Jazz, who whitewashed Los Angeles Lakers 4-0 in the Western
Conference finals, have to overcome a 10-day layoff -- the
second-longest rest in NBA history -- before seeking a revenge for
their defeat last season.
</P>
<P>
"They're waiting, they're hungry and they feel the pain from
when we beat them last year," Jud Buechler said after the Bulls
beat the Indiana Pacers 88-83 Sunday night in Game 7 of the
Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
"We may be a little tired, but our hearts are not tired,"
Jordan said. Looking more like a marathoner stumbling across the
finish line than the soaring, Jordan wound up last night's
showdown with 28 points, 9 rebounds and 8 assists.
</P>
<P>
"He's been the greatest and the playoffs have been his
showcase," Bulls coach Phi Jackson said. "This is one he won't say
is among his greatest, but it still shows the energy and emphasis
he gives this basketball team."
</P>
<P>
But the Bulls are not as overwhelming as they were in the early
1990s, or even two seasons ago when they won an unthinkable 72
games. Besides, the 35-year-old Jordan gets tired and misses shots
and commits errors he never used to.
</P>
<P>
"The ideal situation," Jordan said, "is to sweep every
series. But for a team that's trying to win for the third time
like we are, it's not uncommon to lose focus at times. We
probably came in a little cocky, and with a little swagger, but
nobody's taken anying away from us yet."
</P>
<P>
Maybe the Bulls have a little something for the Jazz, but
Utah had beaten them in both of the team's regular season
meetings.
</P>
<P>
Malone, who beat Jordan in MVP vote last season, won't have to
justify any awards this season. But he'll still be going for the
championship that has eluded him through an otherwise magnificent
13-year career.
</P>
<P>
The Jazz had the second-best home record in the league
(36-5), and their arena is one of the loudest.
</P>
<P>
Pacers coach Larry Bird said:"One time, I had eight days off
waiting for the championship, and there is no way to stay in
game shape."
</P>
<P>
The Jazz will also face problems trying to guard Jordan.
Bryon Russell and Shandon Anderson were given the task, but they
failed to do it well.
</P>
<P>
Coach Jerry Sloan decided not to double-team Jordan at the
end of Game 1 last year, and it cost him.
</P>
<P>
Jordan said:"We still have what we have and an opportunity
to maintain it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
