<HEADLINE> Israel to Attend EU-Mediterranean Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A five-member Israeli delegation
is due to leave Tuesday for Italy to participate a conference of
European Union (EU), North African and Middle East states which
will focus on economic cooperation, an Israeli newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The conference, to be held in Palermo, Sicily Wednesday, is a
follow-up of the 1994 EU-Mediterranean conference in Barcelona
attended by 15 EU member states and 11 countries on the
Mediterranean coast.
</P>
<P>
At that conference, the participating countries held extensive
discussions on ways to improve cooperation in such fields as
culture, economics and security.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry Director-General Eytan Bentsur, who
will head the delegation, was quoted by the Jerusalem Post as
saying that the conference "is not defined as a formal diplomatic
event" and thus the deadlocked Middle East peace process would not
be on its agenda.
</P>
<P>
But Syria and Lebanon are likely to "spare no effort" to bring
this issue before the participants, he said.
</P>
<P>
Libya will be the only North African state excluded from the
conference, which will be chaired by British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook, presumably due to its refusal to hand over to Britain
or United States two suspects implicated in the 1988 Lockerbie
air crash of a Pan American Airlines jet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
