<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Handicapped People Helped to Find Jobs in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Approximately 200,000 handicapped
people in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region have
found jobs by the end of May with the aid of local governments and
various social circles.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 11,000 of them are workers of
the welfare factories, a kind of factories which enjoy
preferential treatment in terms of taxes, the supply of raw
materials, product sales and technical upgrading.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous regional government urged enterprises and other
institutions to attach importance to protection of the disabled
people's rights to subsistence and work.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region has adopted a regulation concerning the
employment of the handicapped, which became effective on January
1, urging local enterprises and work units to employ at least 15
disabled people per thousand of their workforce.
</P>
<P>
To date, some 40,000 disabled people have been employed in
accordance with the regulation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more local handicapped people become self-employed
with the assistance of local governments and various institutions,
according to sources from the Autonomous Regional Federation for
the Disabled. And 150,000 other handicapped people in the region's
rural areas basically have enough to eat and wear.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia has more than 960,000 disabled people, and over
half of them have working abilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People Buying Apartments in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Beijing offices of the China
Construction Bank have been crowded with people applying for home
mortgage loans these days.
</P>
<P>
A man named Cao, a worker of a local construction company,
said, "We're asked to buy public apartments before set dates. As
it's inconvenient to borrow money from relatives, we have to turn
to apply for bank housing loans."
</P>
<P>
The on-going housing reform is to change the welfare-oriented
public housing allocation system. Government departments and
state-owned enterprises are asking their employees who decide to
buy public housing to pay before the end of June. Those who do not
buy housing will have to pay higher rents later.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Zhao, a white-collar workers of a foreign company based in
Beijing, is another kind of clients of the bank. In April, he
bought a flat in Beijing's suburbs at 190,000 yuan (22,890 US
dollars), of which 120,000 yuan were bank loans with an annual
interest of 5.22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under this 10-year-loan arrangement, Mr. Zhao has to pay back
1,285 yuan every month. The loan is guaranteed by a local
insurance company for which Zhao paid 3,516 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Actually, many people have not made up their mind yet as
whether to buy or to continue to rent apartments. They go to the
bank just for consultancy.
</P>
<P>
Some low- and middle-income earners say that they can hardly
afford the 30 percent first installment for a new home. Others say
they can not pay for the over 1,000 yuan every month for a
ten-year housing loan.
</P>
<P>
At present, commercial apartments in Beijing, Shanghai, and
Guangzhou cost between 3,000 and 4,000 yuan per square meter and
in other cities around 2,000 yuan. Many people say they would
rather wait for the price to fall before deciding to buy an
apartment of their own. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
