<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia to Spend More on Internet Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Asian companies are expected to
spend more on Internet-intranet projects despite their economic
difficulties, said research company IDC Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand InfoTech Weekly quoted on Tuesday IDC Managing
Director Dennis Philbin as saying that while Asian companies are
cutting spending on information technology (IT), they are
increasing the portion spent on Internet-intranet projects from
6.2 percent in 1997 to 20 percent of IT spending by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Singapore-based Philbin said Asian companies have indicated to
IDC that though they need to cut costs, the threat of global
competition means they must forge better links with customers and
suppliers using Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
In response to the crisis, they will focus on doing more with
their existing computer systems instead of installing new
hardware.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Asia-Pacific region excluding Japan spent 50.2
billion U.S. dollars on IT, up 10 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to grow to 88.2 billion U.S. dollars by
2002, with China witnessing the highest growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
