<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Groundwater Level Drops in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The groundwater level of Beijing
has been dropping in recent years, causing cracks and dislocation
in some buildings.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, the groundwater level was 1.6 meters
lower than that in the previous year, and 5.52 meters lower than
that in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that excessive pumping was the main cause of the
consecutive dropping of the water level, noting that the decrease
of rainfall accelerates the pumping.
</P>
<P>
Last year's rainfall was only 403 mm, 32 percent down from
the annual average of 600 mm, while the city pumped a total of
2,704 million cubic meters of groundwater, 254 million cubic
meters more than the annual average.
</P>
<P>
So far, the groundwater reserve has decreased by 2,826
million cubic meters, compared to that in 1980. As a result, the
ground level of Beijing sank at a speed of 10 to 20 mm. every year.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has been long suffering from a severe water
shortage. The average water resource per capita is less than 300
cubic meters, one-eighth of the country's average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
