<HEADLINE> Arrest of Leading Mafia Boss Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Italian authorities Monday praised
law enforcement agneices and officers for their efforts to capture
Salvatore Pillera, a leading Mafia boss in Catania of eastern
Sicily.
</P>
<P>
Salvatore Pillera, the head of the Cursoti family, was arrested
at his home in the Mesima district and charged with Mafia
association and suspected involvement in two murder cases in 1982
and 1984.
</P>
<P>
Pillera was released from prison on August 22, 1996, after
serving eight years of a twelve-year sentence for Mafia
association.
</P>
<P>
Police said following his early release for "good behavior,"
Pillera brought together the Cursoti and the Santapaolo family,
the two rival gangs in Catania. The two families had been engaged
in a bloody feud for a decade for the control of crime in
Catania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
