<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Might Reach NATO Standards by 2010: Ex-U.S. Adverser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine could not "objectively" tally
with the criteria of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
until the year 2010, said former U.S. national security adviser
Zbigniew Brzezinski on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Brzezinski, who served as national security adviser from 1977
to 1981, said at a press conference here that a country seeking
NATO membership should meet four standards: stable democracy,
well-managed free market economy, efficient supervision of the
military by the civilians and freedom from border disputes.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has reached two of the four standards, Brzezinski said,
admitting that objective attainment of the standards did not
mean that Ukraine would subjectively decide to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
Leading a delegation of U.S. politicians, Brzezinski arrived
Ukraine on Friday for an eight-day tour.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma, the
former U.S. national security adviser suggested the Ukrainian
parliament elect a middle-of-the-roader speaker in order to win
more support from the West and international finance organizations.
</P>
<P>
Brzezinski also told Kuchma that his visit is connected with
the United States' long-term policies towards Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, he also met the Secretary of the State
Committee on Security and Defense, Vladimir Gorbulin, and Foreign
Minister Boris Tarasyuk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Willing to Meet Indian, Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina is willing to visit New Delhi and Islamabad as soon as
possible to discuss with her Indian and Pakistani counterparts the
situation arising from the recent nuclear tests, a Foreign
Ministry official told Xinhua Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In separate letters to Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee and Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, Hasina said,
"Personally I would be happy to visit your great country at an
early date to discuss the situation arising out of nuclear tests
(conducted by India and Pakistan in May) and all issues of mutual
concern."
</P>
<P>
The letters were handed over to Indian and Pakistani high
commissioners in Dhaka, who were separately called to the Foreign
Ministry Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Hasina was writing in reply to the letters she received from
her Indian and Pakistani counterparts separately in which they
explained their respective positions with regard to nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that the imperative and priority for the countries
of the region were development and cooperation among themselves so
as to ensure a better quality of life and standard of living for
the South Asian people.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that an arms race involving nuclear weapons and
missile technology would be detrimental to these objectives and it
would also affect the atmosphere of cooperation and friendship.
</P>
<P>
"Our main concern nationally, at this point of time, is to
combat the pervasive problems of grinding poverty,
underdevelopment, disease, hunger and environmental degradation,"
she stressed in the letters.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that "every country will decide its own security
perceptions and take measures accordingly," she expressed her view
that "nuclear weapons did not enhance a country's security in the
post-Cold War and indeed, could diminish it."
</P>
<P>
There was a great realization the world over of the need for
nuclear disarmament, she added.
</P>
<P>
In her letters, the Bangladeshi prime minister also expressed
her confidence that all differences and problems could be resolved
through dialogue and discussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Forecasts Zero Growth for Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian tourism industry will
see a zero growth this year because of the ongoing monetary
crisis, a government official was quoted by local press Tuesday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
It is practically impossible for the country's tourism sector
to record any growth this year, Director General of Tourism in the
Ministry of Tourism, Arts and Culture Andi Mappisammeng said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's tourism sector managed to bring in foreign exchange
of no less than 6.6 billion U.S. dollars last year, and such an
amount of foreign exchange was earned through the arrival of over
5 million foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
According to Mappisammeng, the tourism sector had experienced a
minus 15.4 percent growth rate in the first three months of this
year. As a result, foreign exchange earnings from the sector
dropped by 20.2 percent compared with that in the first three
months of last year.
</P>
<P>
It is feared that if such a situation continues until the end
of this year, the tourism sector will not even be able to record
zero growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that if the economic situation does not
improve in the coming months, it is likely that at the end of this
year the tourism sector will see a minus 15 percent growth rate.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian tourism industry has suffered from the problems
of forest fires, economic crisis as well as unrest which shook the
capital and several other cities last month.
</P>
<P>
If things did improve in the second semester of 1998, the
sector still had the opportunity to see a brighter prospect as the
month of July is usually described as the beginning of the holiday
season, observers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
