<HEADLINE> Bosnia Begins to Register Voters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The registration of voters over
Bosnia-Herzegovina for the upcoming general elections, scheduled
to take place on September 12 and 13, began on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Croatian News Agency reports from Sarajevo, Robert
Barry, chief representative of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), and his deputy in charge of the
electoral process, Linda Edgeworth, stressed on Monday that the
1991 census still remained the basis for the list of voters.
</P>
<P>
All those whose names are not on the census will have to
provide evidence that they are indeed citizens of
Bosnia-Herzegovina, and the evidence will be examined by OSCE
supervisors, Edgeworth said.
</P>
<P>
Besides 235 registration offices in Bosnia-Herzegovina, 35 have
been opened in Yugoslavia, and 30 in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The registration of voters is conducted by local staff, but
their work is under close scrutiny by OSCE representatives who
arrived especially for this task.
</P>
<P>
The registration will last until June 27 and is applicable only
to citizens of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
