<HEADLINE> Liberal, Conservative Candidates Restart Election Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Horacio Serpa of the
ruling Liberal Party and Andres Pastrana of the Conservative Party
Monday renewed their election campaign efforts for the runoff
election on June 21.
</P>
<P>
With 98 percent of the ballots counted, Serpa led Pastrana in
Sunday's election with 34.64 percent to 34.32 percent.
</P>
<P>
Neither candidate, however, received more than 50 percent of
the ballots during the election.
</P>
<P>
Independent candidate Noemi Sanin was third in the polls with
2.8 million votes, or 27 percent of the vote. She received the
greatest number of votes ever for an independent candidate in a
country where the two main parties have alternately held power for
50 years.
</P>
<P>
Sanin released her 2.8 million voters for the runoff election,
but said she would announce her personal preference in days to
come. She also announced the creation of a new political party
triggered by the necessity for change in the country.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here say that most of Sanin's followers identify more
with the Conservative Party than with the Liberal Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
