<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Justice Minister on Possible Travel Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Justice Minister Muladi
said here Monday that his ministry is ready to impose an overseas
travel ban on former president Soeharto and his family upon the
request of the Attorney General's Office or the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"So far, the finance minister has not asked me to prevent them
from traveling abroad. But I will directly order the immigration
authorities to do so in case of a request from the finance
minister," Muladi was quoted by local press Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Attorney General Ismudjoko told reporters
here Monday that his office would not impose a travel ban on
Soeharto or any of his family members. He pointed out that his
office had received guarantees from the Soeharto family that they
would not leave the country.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto resigned from the presidency on May 21 under heavy
pressure from the people demanding for total reforms in political,
economic and legal fields.
</P>
<P>
The former president has been accused of amassing tens of
billions of U.S. dollars from corruption, collusion and numerous
shady business deals. The Indonesian Business Data Center
estimated the wealth of Soeharto and his family at 200 trillion
rupiah (about 20 billion U.S. dollars),
</P>
<P>
Asked about the list of the Soeharto family's wealth
circulating around, Muladi said it must be checked first.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that he supports any investigation on the
Soeharto family's wealth, but this must go through proper
procedures. The investigation must be conducted fairly and
honestly and thus there must be a national policy on conducting
it.
</P>
<P>
The government has commenced an investigation into the personal
assets of Soeharto, along with several other ousted government
officials, Attorney General Soedjono C. Atmonegoro said.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not disclose when the investigation commenced,
nor did he disclose specific timeframe allocated to the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
"The investigations are being conducted under the principle of
the presumption of innocence," Soedjono said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Attorney General Ismudjoko explained that while the
investigation was very urgent, it would take some time to complete
as the work would involve the checking of many documents related
to a large number of business deals.
</P>
<P>
"The former president may be summoned, if necessary, to verify
and check evidence in cooperation with other state agencies", he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
