<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Gap Between Northern, Southern Italy Widening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The economic gap between northern and
southern Italy continues to widen with an economic growth of 1.7
percent in the central and northern regions last year and 0.9
percent in the south.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Development Institute Svimez said in a report
Monday that in 1994-1997, the economic growth was 0.75 percent in
the southern areas, while areas in the north grew 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Gross fixed investments fell by an average of 1.5 percent
annually in the south, but they rose by 3.3 percent in the north.
</P>
<P>
In the past four years, 179,000 jobs were lost in southern
Italy, while only 92,000 were lost in the north.
</P>
<P>
The report said consumption in the south jumped 3.1 percent
this year, while rising by 7.5 percent in the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Restructuring to Bring Capital Inflow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bangkok, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand will speed up
the process of debt restructuring to attract capital inflow into
the country, the bank's governor Chatu Mongol Sonakul has said.
</P>
<P>
He said the central bank will let the debts owed by 56 troubled
financial firms go under the hammer as soon as possible so that it
can keep the debt restructuring process going.
</P>
<P>
"If we can restructure these debts, the expected amount of
foreign capital will flow into the country," said Chatu Mongol,
quoted by the Nation daily Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the new capital, in the form of joint-venture firms
such as steel or property loan management companies, is expected
to flow into Thailand during the next couple of months.
</P>
<P>
He said such inflow will help strengthen the local currency
baht and ease inflationary pressure to a certain extend.
</P>
<P>
Chatu Mongol did not disclose the amount of debts belonging to
the firms. But earlier media reports put the figure at more than 3
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Chatu Mongol said, the central bank is now
undertaking a study on debt restructuring to meet international
standards in accordance with the Office of the Currency Controller
(OCC), a supervisory department of the U.S. Federal Reserves
overlooking financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Required by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Thailand has
to go ahead with the debt restructuring and re-estimation of
collateral before mid-June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
