<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Car Smugglers Arrested in Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian police have broken up a
well-organized international car smuggling ring, arresting 12
suspects and seizing 12 cars.
</P>
<P>
The cars were first stolen from Quebec, Canada, and then loaded
in containers, three cars in each, before being transported by sea
to Bulgaria, said an officer of the National Service for Organized
Crime Control (NSOCC).
</P>
<P>
Fake documents claimed the sealed containers were full of
fiberglass destined for a plant in Sofia.
</P>
<P>
The seizure included such brand names as Mercedes Benz, Volvo
and Nissan, each of which would cost up to 60,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The cars were sold to two dealers in Sofia, who had already
sold some of them, taking deposits of 30,000 dollars. Some cars
were destined for re-export to former Soviet republics via the
Bulgarian Black Sea port of Varna, the NSOCC said.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian police also contributed to the success of the
operation by providing support to their Bulgarian counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The alleged head of the criminal ring, a Bulgarian migrant in
Canada and now living in Bulgaria, was still at large. The police
have issued a national arrest warrant to bring him to justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
