<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Enjoys International Balance of Payments in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The balance sheet of international
payments released Monday by the State Administration of Foreign
Exchange (SAFE) indicates that China achieved favorable balance
of payments in 1997 for a fourth year in succession.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that in 1997 both the current account and the
capital account had surplus, foreign exchange reserves rose
sharply, and payment ability further was enhanced.
</P>
<P>
In the year, the current account had a surplus of 29.72 billion
US dollars. According to international accounting standards,
China's exports totaled 182.67 billion US dollars, up 20.9 percent
from the previous year, while imports totaled 136.45 billion US
dollars, up 3.8 percent, with a surplus of 24.58 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The capital account had a surplus of 22.96 billion US
dollars. Direct investment remained the main form of foreign
capital inflow, with the net investment from overseas reaching
44.24 billion US dollars, up 10.1 percent. This shows that
overseas investors still favor China's economic prospects
despite the financial crisis in some Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
1997 also saw a big progress for China's direct fund-raising
from the international capital market, with the net inflow of
securities investment reaching 6.8 billion US dollars, up 290.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
Trade surplus and capital inflow have pushed up the country's
foreign exchange reserves. By the end of 1997, China's foreign
exchange reserves had reached 139.9 billion US dollars, an
increase of 34.9 billion US dollars oover the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
