<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's First Prime Minister Visits Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese leaders and visiting
Cambodian First Prime Minister Ung Huot have agreed to improve
bilateral ties by enhancing cooperation and friendship.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot arrived in Hanoi on Monday to pay a two-day official
visit to Vietnam at the invitation of his Vietnamese counterpart
Phan Van Khai.
</P>
<P>
After official talks with Khai, the first prime minister met
with Vietnamese Communist Party chief Le Kha Phieu and Vietnamese
President Tran Duc Luong.
</P>
<P>
They focused their discussions on detailed measures that would
strengthen existing friendly relations and cooperation between the
two countries and exchanged views on regional and international
issues of common concern, the Vietnam News Agency (VNA) said.
</P>
<P>
Khai said he hoped the coming general election in Cambodia
would be successful and stabilize the domestic situation, so the
people and government could concentrate efforts on building a
prosperous nation.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot expressed his admiration for the economic achievements
made by the Vietnamese people in the recent period, especially
their success in fighting natural calamities and overcoming the
negative impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Khai affirmed that Vietnam would continue to support Cambodia
in its endeavor to join the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations(ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
The leaders of both countries expressed the hope for the
establishment of "a peaceful, friendly border" that would
reaffirm the need "for continued respect of treaties and
agreements on roads and sea ways that were signed by the two
countries in 1982, 1983 and 1985," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' experts agreed to hold a second round of
meetings related to the border in late June.
</P>
<P>
Khai and Ung Huot also witnessed the signing of three documents
between the two governments, including an agreement on land
transport cooperation, a protocol on information cooperation, and
a memorandum of understanding on the fight against drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot will return to Cambodia on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
