<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major recent
economic news briefs in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- A third nuclear reactor with a capacity of 1,300
megawatts is to be built at Mexico's nuclear electric plant to
meet the growing demand for energy.
</P>
<P>
The plant currently generates 675 megawatts, 70 percent of
which is supplied to the state of Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Wholesale prices of the products manufactured in
Uruguay increased 1.3 percent in the first five months of this
year, the Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
The price hikes was resulted from the inflation rise.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's trade deficit amounted to about 621 million
U.S. dollars in Chile in the first quarter of this year with 5.6
billion dollars of exports and 6.2 billion dollars of imports.
</P>
<P>
Chile's Central Bank said the deficit mainly resulted from the
reduction of the copper price in international markets.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil will import 2.2. million tons of grains,
after registering a fall in the harvest of cereals this year.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay and Argentina are increasing their exports to Brazil to
1.2 million tons at the end of this year, while the United States
and some Asian countries will export one million tons of grain to
help meet Brazil's domestic demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
