<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More NATO Expansion May Harm Europe's Stability: Primakov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Further expansion of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) could threaten Europe's
stability, visiting Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Maksimovich
Primakov warned on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference here that although Russia has no say
on the policies of other countries, it opposes NATO's eastward
expansion, especially toward the former Soviet Union's member
countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russia enjoys good relations with NATO and is
willing to take an active part in cooperating with this
organization through various channels, Primakov noted.
</P>
<P>
On Russia's relations with Latvia, he reiterated the call for
Latvia to fully implement the proposals by Max van der Stoel, the
human rights representative of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, to normalize and develop bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Primakov welcomed Finland's proposal for Northern Dimensions
within the European Union aimed at strengthening the Nordic area's
economic cooperation with Russia and the Baltic countries.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped the policy would help Russia get loans from
the European Investment Bank to improve transportation in
northwestern Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister arrived in Helsinki last Friday
for a three-day official visit to further develop the "model"
relations with Finland as well as cooperation with the EU, since
Finland is to serve as the EU's presidency in the second half of
1999.
</P>
<P>
Primakov had several talks with his Finnish counterpart Tarja
Halonen. He also met with Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari and
Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen before leaving for Sweden on Monday
afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
