<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Cut Down 11,500 Government Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian government is to make
more than 159,000 public sector workers redundant this year in an
effort to trim public spending.
</P>
<P>
Local government staff will be cut by 11 percent, or 148,000,
while central government is to shed 11,500 workers from various
levels.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the government is aiming to cut
administration expenditure in order to reduce budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
In May, the Ukrainian government passed a resolution to limit
its 1998 budget deficit to 2.5 percent of the projected gross
domestic product (GDP), that is 2.34 billion cryvna (1.14 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the following six months, Ukraine is planning to cut the
number of staff whose salaries depend on annual budget from three
million to 2.6 million. By the end of 2000, the number will be
limited to 2.2 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico City to fight Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Mexico City, known as the
world's most polluted, will apply strict measures to fight
environmental pollution, Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said in an interview that the most strict measures will be
applied to vehicles and industries, the worst pollution sources of
the city.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the municipal authorities have plans to
provide credits to help substitute vehicles of the 1989 and
earlier models, yet no resources are now available.
</P>
<P>
He noted that steps will be taken at both the national and city
levels to reduce pollutant content in the air.
</P>
<P>
The city government will also monitor the implementation of
environmental programs, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
