<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Inflation Rate Hits 10.2 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's inflation rate in May
hit 10.2 percent compared with a rate of just 4.3 percent in the
same month last year, and 10.1 percent in April, the Bangkok Post
Tuesday quoted the Commerce Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, inflation, as measured by the
consumer price index (CPI), was running at 9.5 percent for the
first five months of this year, compared with 4.3 percent in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Prices of food and beverage items rose by 0.8 percent in May,
and non-food prices were up by 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In May, prices declined in jasmine rice and fruit, but rose for
fresh vegetables, eggs, seafood, raw chicken and dairy products.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, prices of some goods and services such as
electricity charges, transport fees and cooking gas remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The May inflation rate was up by 0.5 percent over April, slower
than the 0.7 percent month-on-month rise recorded in April, 1.1
percent in March, 0.7 percent in February and 1.1 percent in
January, said Vithun Tulyanond, deputy director-general of the
Business Economics Department.
</P>
<P>
Vithun also said that the country's annual inflation rate for
the year is expected to be less than 10.5 percent as projected by
the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
