<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gebrselassie Breaks 10,000m World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Haile Gebrselassie of Eithiopia
took the spotlight by setting the 10,000 meters world record in 26
minutes 22.75 seconds at the IAAF Grand Prix II meeting in
Hengelo, Netherlands, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gebrselassie, Olympic champion over the distance, eclipsed the
previous record of 26:27.85 set by Kenyan Paul Tergat on August 27
last year at the Ivo Van Damme Memorial meeting in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
It was the third world record Gebrselassie run at the Dutch
meet, and was the third time to break the 10,000m record in his
career.
</P>
<P>
Wilson Boit Kipketer of Kenya won the 3,000m in a time of seven
minutes 36.05 seconds, also the best of the year so far.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Bernard Barmassai, who set last year's best time in the
3,000m steeplechase, clocked 8:11.57, 15 seconds outside his own
world record.
</P>
<P>
Morocco's Hicham El Guerrouj won the 1,500m in a year's best of
3:31.19, three seconds away from Algerian Nouredinne Morceli's
world record.
</P>
<P>
There also were world best times of the year for Hungary's
Gabriella Szabo in the women's 1,500m in 4:02.89 and Morocco's
Zahra Ouaziz in the women's 3,000m 8:30.43.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
