<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Negotiations Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States expressed its
deep concern on Monday about escalating violence in the Serbian
province of Kosovo and urged continuous negotiations to end the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the way to solve the problem is at the
negotiating table not the battlefield," State Department spokesman
James Rubin told a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
Reports say that thousands of refugees from Kosovo streamed
into neighboring Albania on Monday to escape some of the deadliest
fighting in months.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was trying to confirm the number of casualties,
reports of executions and numbers fleeing, but this was proving
difficult because authorities have closed off key areas of the
province, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that Kosovo Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova
told President Bill Clinton in a meeting on Friday and Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright on Saturday he was prepared to engage
in continuous talks.
</P>
<P>
Rubin stressed the administration hoped that a political
solution can be found through such continuous discussions given
the urgency of the situation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration, saying that it does not support
Kosovo's full independence from Serbia, upholds that the Kosovo
Albanians, which account 90 percent of the population in the
province, should be given more autonomy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
