<HEADLINE> China Out of Contention Despite Win over Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BREMEN, Germany, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Defending runner-up China
edged Japan 94-93 but didn't make the quarter-finals on Monday,
the last day of the Women's World Basketball Championship second
run competition.
</P>
<P>
China won only one of five games and needed to beat Japan by at
least six points for a possible quarter-final berth.
</P>
<P>
Japan has a 2-4 record and is waiting the outcome of
Spain-Lithuania match. It could qualify if Lithuania wins late
Monday.
</P>
<P>
China opened with 22-12 and ended the first half with a 49-37
lead.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese 68-58 second half lead was erased by Japan as it
posted a 16-6 run to make it 74-all.
</P>
<P>
After six ties, Yang Li scored a three-pointer to put China
ahead 94-89 with 20 seconds left, but Japan, the 12th place
finisher four years ago, narrowed the gap with Chikako Murakami's
four straight points including two free-throws.
</P>
<P>
"We played very well in the first half, but not in the second,"
Chinese coach Ma Yuenan said. "We had poor defense and let the
Japanese score eight three-pointers at the second half."
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese gave us a lesson," Ma added.
</P>
<P>
China overcame Japan 82-65 four years ago, but was beaten both
in the 1996 Olympic Games and the Asian Championship last year.
</P>
<P>
Mikiko Hagiwara led five double-figure Japanese with a
game-high 29 points. Akemi Okazato scored 20, Takako Kato and
center Noriko Hamaguchi got 15 apeice and Chikako Murakami 14.
</P>
<P>
Center Ma Chengqing led China with 23 point and 7 rebounds,
followed by Mao Bo's 21 and Liang Xin's 20.
</P>
<P>
China will take part in the classification matches for 9-12
places starting from June 4 in Berlin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
