<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netherlands Lift Men's Hockey World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Hosts the Netherlands had to
overcome a two-goal deficit on Monday before beating Spain to win
the men's field hockey World Cup in Utrecht.
</P>
<P>
The win was the third for the Dutch who had lifted the trophy
in the 1973 and 1990 tournaments as well.
</P>
<P>
Spain, which entered its first World Cup finals since 1971,
surprised the Olympic titlists with two field goals through Jordi
Arnau and Victor Pujol in the 18th and 55th minutes.
</P>
<P>
Dutch captain Stephan Veen pumped back some confidence into the
host side with a 58th-minute goal which helped the Dutch to find
its rhythm of play that soon materialized into the equalizer.
</P>
<P>
Bram Lomans saved the Olympic champions the humiliation to lose
on home turf to its Olympic underdogs by levelling the game in the
61st minute and forced play into the golden-goal sudden-death
overtime.
</P>
<P>
Lomans' shot off a penalty short corner just beat the reach of
Spanish goalkeeper Ramon Jufresa.
</P>
<P>
Both sides played cautiously in overtime until Teun de Nooijer
volleyed in a rebound for the match winner from keeper Jufresa who
dived to block out a shot from a penalty corner 13 minutes into
extra play.
</P>
<P>
Germany nipped Australia 1-0 earlier in the day to finish third
in the 12-team tournament while holders Pakistan defeated England
4-2 to land fifth, followed by South Korea that beat Canada with
another 4-2 scoresheet.
</P>
<P>
India downed New Zealand 1-0 to place ninth and Malaysia beat
Poland 5-4 on Sunday to wrap up the 11th position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
