<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Officials Asked to Use Plain English </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
Monday announced a directive requiring bureaucrats to use plain
English and avoid jargon words in documents.
</P>
<P>
Starting October 1, officials are requested to use common,
everyday words, active, not passive voice, and short sentences,
according to the directive.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton ordered the change, which applies to all
new federal documents, other than regulations.
</P>
<P>
Federal regulations will be required to use plain English from
the beginning of next year.
</P>
<P>
"By using plain language, we send a clear message about what
the government is doing, what it requires and what services it
offers," Clinton wrote in announcing the initiative.
</P>
<P>
"Plain language saves the government and the private sector
time, effort and money," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Gore told a group of small business owners from around the
country, "Short is better than long. Active is better than
passive.... Clarity helps advance understanding."
</P>
<P>
Gore said that government rules that took 72 words to explain
will be chopped to around six. Unfamiliar phrases will be
simplified.
</P>
<P>
He appreciated the Small Business Administration and the
Veterans Benefit Administration, which have made great progress in
rewriting their rules into plain English.
</P>
<P>
The Securities and Exchange Commission took the lead in cutting
jargon and convoluted language and began developing a plain
English rule several years ago with the mutual fund industry.
</P>
<P>
The commission adopted a rule in January requiring that key
sections of mutual fund prospectuses and similar financial
documents be written simply and clearly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S, Bahrain Welcome Iran's "Moderate Tone" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Bahraini Emir Sheik Isa bin Salman al Khalifa Monday welcomed an
"emerging moderate tone" in recent statements by Iran.
</P>
<P>
Clinton held one-hour talks with the Bahraini leader at the
White House and they issued a joint statement, saying they
"welcomed the emerging moderate tone in Iran's statements." They
said they awaited signs of that moderation being reflected in
Iran's actions and relations with other nations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has expressed optimism about the prospect for change in
Iran since President Mohammad Khatami was elected last year and
offered to open a dialogue with the United States.
</P>
<P>
There have been several cultural and athletic exchanges,
including reciprocal visits this year by Iranian and American
wrestling teams.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also discussed with the emir of Bahrain their economic
relations and the nuclear arms race between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In their joint statement, the two leaders also called upon Iraq
to fully implement all U.N. Security Council resolutions,
"including full disclosure of its weapons of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
They stressed that the U.N. resolutions on Iraqi weapons
inspections "must be enforced."
</P>
<P>
Bahrain is a key U.S. ally in the Gulf. It is home to the
Navy's 5th Fleet of 15 warships and about 1,500 U.S. service
members.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. Air Force fleet of fighters, bombers and tankers that
has been on duty in Bahrain for several months is due to leave
this week. The aircraft were part of a U.S. buildup of forces in
the Gulf during a confrontation with Iraq over U.N. weapons
inspections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
