<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Storms, Tornadoes Kill 17 People in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Powerful storms and tornadoes in
the northern Plains, upper Midwest and the Northeast of the United
States during the weekend killed at least 17 people, destroyed
hundreds of homes and businesses and shut down power for more than
1.3 million people.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday night, a tornado destroyed the town of Spencer,
South Dakota, killing six people and injuring some 150 others,
while three people died in Wisconsin and another three in Michigan
in storms.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday night, storms tore from Pennsylvania through New
England. Two men were killed in Massachusetts when a falling tree
crushed their car. One died in New York and two people were killed
in Pennsylvania in the storms, an Associated Press report said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
More than 900,000 homes and businesses lost power in Minnesota,
Wisconsin and Michigan, with 330,000 in Pennsylvania and thousands
more blacked out in Vermont, Massachusetts, Connecticut and
Kentucky. More than 130,000 homes in New York state were still
waiting for power restoration Monday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A tornado was attributed to the death of a teen-age girl and
the injuries of 30 others in Salisbury, Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
In Wisconsin, falling trees killed a 3-year-old boy and a man
in Wisconsin, while in Mechanicville, New York, about 15 homes
were heavily damaged by a possible tornado, and a dozen people
were injured.
</P>
<P>
There were reports of four tornadoes south of Syracuse and 18
near Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the storms to a collision between a cool,
dry air mass from Canada and hot, moist air over the northern
Plains, Midwest, and the Great Lakes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980602.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Hits Another 7-Year High Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar Monday hit its
third consecutive seven-year high against the yen amid worries
about further weakness in the economy of Japanese and other Asian
markets.
</P>
<P>
The dollar fell against the mark as the German currency
strengthened because of the yen's weakness.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 139.70 yen,
up from 138.90 yen late Friday. The last time the dollar was near
Monday's closing level was June 24, 1991, when it reached 139.82.
The dollar hit seven-year trading day highs Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was changing hands at 1.7781 marks, down from
1.7955.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index fell 2.23 percent Monday
and the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to a record low of 1.155 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday:
1.4758 Swiss francs, down from 1.4825; 5.9615 French francs, down
from 5.9880; 1,751.00 Italian lire, down from 1,759.00; and 1.4580
Canadian dollars, up from 1.4567.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6407 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6316 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
