<HEADLINE> U.S. Outlines Purpose of Geneva Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Monday
that a foreign ministers meeting in Geneva due on Thursday will
discuss how to work out a concerted strategy to stop the nuclear
arms race between India and Pakistan, but not press for sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"This is not an attempt to gather support from China, France
and Russia and the United Kingdom for the draconian sanctions the
United States has imposed," State Department spokesman James Rubin
told a briefing.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva meeting will be attended by the foreign ministers of
Britain, China, France, Russia, and the United States -- the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"The immediate focus of the meeting will be to consider ways to
reduce tensions between India and Pakistan and to try to avoid the
kind of provocative steps that have been taken in recent days and
weeks," Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting will also examine ways... (how to) bring greater
stability and security to South Asia, including steps that can be
taken to encourage dialogue and reconciliation between India and
Pakistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We want to discuss ways to prompt the countries in the region
to avoid further provocative steps -- including additional missile
and nuclear tests, inflammatory rhetoric, and additional military
activity of a more conventional type," he added.
</P>
<P>
But the five countries will not invite representatives of India
and Pakistan to the meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the long term the United States wants a solution to the
problem of Kashmir, the divided mountain territory that has been
the major cause of tension, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The combination of the political tensions, including over
Kashmir, with the nuclear testing that has occurred is a volatile
combination, and... it's time to get on with resolving this
problem," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
