<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Optimistic About Russia's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Treasury official
expressed prudent optimism Monday about Russia's economy, saying
the country was on the right track with its reforms despite of the
current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Mark Medish, deputy assistant secretary of the Treasury, made
the remarks at the Smithsonian Institution in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"I am bullish about the Russian Bear," said Medish. "I am
prudently bullish."
</P>
<P>
Russia was "basically doing the right things" to improve the
growth and vitality of its economy and had undertaken a number of
important reforms, such as privatization and legal and regulatory
changes, said Medish.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, worries about the economy and the stability of the
ruble prompted a more than 10 percent slide in the Russian stock
market.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe that to restore investors' confidence,
billions of aid from international financial institutions would be
needed.
</P>
<P>
Medish described the nation as a victim of contagion from the
battered Asian economies of South Korea, Indonesia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia should pay close attention to the lessons
learned from the Asian crisis, such as the need for governments to
share information with the outside world, even when the news was
bad.
</P>
<P>
Moving as quickly as possible on economic reforms would help
Russia weather the crisis by stemming growing speculation about a
currency devaluation, noted Medish.
</P>
<P>
"To use a basketball metaphor, Team Russia faces a shot clock,"
Medish said. "It needs to sink a three pointer, preferably with
some foul shots to boot." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
