<HEADLINE> News Analysis:  Why Detained Kuanda Is Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's former President Kenneth
Kaunda, who has been detained for over five months and charged
with misprison of treason was released by the Lusaka High Court
Monday.
</P>
<P>
About 10 minutes after the opening of the trial of 82 accused
coupists, Attorney General Bovaventure Mutale declared the state
withdrew all the charges against Kaunda and Judge Japhet Banda
set him free.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, also leader of Zambia's largest opposition United
National Independent Party (UNIP), was first arrested last
December for alleged involvement in a foiled military coup last
October but transferred to house arrest several days later under
international pressure.
</P>
<P>
Investigations into Kaunda's connections with the coup has
never stopped. The police charged him with treason in January
this year but one month later formally charged him with misprison
of treason together with his security chief, accusing them of
concealing the knowledge of last October's coup plot.
</P>
<P>
However, the former president who led Zambia to independence
from Britain in 1964 and ruled the country for 27 years has been
denying the charges and insisted that he is "innocent" and always
described his arrest as a "malicious" political action against
him.
</P>
<P>
Abnormalities emerged at or out of the court Monday. The
supporters of the ruling Movement for Muti-Party Democracy (MMD)
who have usually attended such court proceedings in the past,
were absent from the scene, apparently for fear of clashing with
Kaunda's supporters.
</P>
<P>
Several prosecutors including Legal Minister Vincent Malambo
and Minister of State House Eric Silwamba who are supposed to
appear at the court were also absent from the trial, and there is
no witness to be called to testify against the accused.
</P>
<P>
All these suggested that there was a premediated backstage
deal. Some western diplomats believed that the release of Kaunda
was brokered by South African President Nelson Mandela, who used
to be Kaunda's guest in Lusaka during his struggle against South
Africa's apartheid under the white rule.
</P>
<P>
While Zambia's leading independent newspaper, The Post, quoted
Monday State House and UNIP sources as saying that President
Fredrick Chiluba has offered to release Kaunda from prison and
instruct Attorney General Bonaventure Mutale to enter a nolle
prosequi against the former head of state if he agrees to step
down from politics.
</P>
<P>
But in an interview with Xinhua immediately after Kaunda
walked to freedom, Professor Patrick Mvunga who once served as
vice-president in the Kuanda government and now a state counsel
in the defense team said that the release is a natural thing
because his client is "innocent", stressing that the state failed
to gather efficient evidence to prove Kaunda guilty.
</P>
<P>
Then what are Chiluba's considerations to Kaunda's release?
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that by this move, Chiluba can "kill two
birds with one stone." On the one hand, he can appease the
western donors and the southern African leaders that pushed him
to release Kaunda soon after the "Father of Nation" was arrested.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Chiluba may leave Kaunda alone and let him
run his course or be destroyed by some ambitious leaders in his
own party which has been bogged down in an internal fighting over
the party's leadership.
</P>
<P>
Anyhow, released Kaunda will not thank Chiluba who took power
from him in the 1991 general elections and was re-elected for
another five year term.
</P>
<P>
As Kuanda put it immediately after he walked freely out of the
court that he was born an "politician" and he will continue to be
a "thorn" in the side of Chiluba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
