<HEADLINE> Greece Criticizes British Newspaper Report About Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday criticized a British
newspaper report about a plan to evacuate British citizens from
Cyprus if Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles are installed
in the divided island republic.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Times newspaper said in a report that London would
evacuate its citizens from Cyprus if the latter installed later
this year the missiles.
</P>
<P>
He described the report as "tendentious," saying that the aim
of the report was to pressure the Cyprus government into not
installing the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Any such pressure would bring no result, he said, adding that
Greece would fully support Cyprus in its efforts to strengthen its
defense.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greece's Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos Monday
said it was regrettable that certain countries which supposedly
wanted to contribute to the settlement of the Cyprus problem
should exert pressure on Nicosia not to install the missiles.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that if those countries really wanted positive
developments in the Cyprus problem, they should focus their
efforts in the direction of Turkey which was responsible for the
existence of a threat and destabilization.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greece's ambassador to Britain lodged
Monday a protest with the British Foreign Office over the report.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an abortive-coup
backed by Athens.
</P>
<P>
To bolster its defense, Cyprus had signed with Russia a
contract to purchase the S-300 missiles, but with the nearing of
the installation of the missiles, the tension in Cyprus has been
escalating due to Turkey's threat to stop Cyprus from doing so.
</P>
</TEXT>
